\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\uc2  muddles through adverse conditions. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,722 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Vincent Lingga, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  entered 2001 amid heightened political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the increasingly erratic leadership of then president Abdurrahman Wahid, a decline in the government's credibility and a weakened global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government's relationship with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) became prickly after the IMF decided in December 2000 to postpone the third US$400 million disbursement of its extended loan facility due to frequent slippages in promised reform measures and several \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reversals. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank delivered another blow to the market's already low levels of confidence in the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects by deciding in January to slash its annual loan commitment from $1.2 billion to a mere $400 million, citing the government's huge existing debt burden as the main reason for the new lending \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  However, the real reason was the government's failure to keep up with its reform commitments, particularly those related to the establishment of high fiduciary standards in \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  management and procurement systems, and its anti-corruption drive. \par \par \uc2  The cash-starved government received further punishment in April when the World Bank canceled the disbursement of $300 million in social safety net loans due to what it considered the slow pace of meaningful changes in government institutions and the bureaucratic culture. But what really motivated the cancellation was the Bank's heartfelt concern that the funds would be wasted through corruption. \par \par \uc2  The nasty combination of a weakening currency, growing \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , increasing inflationary pressures and consequently rising \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , along with a slump in exports, stifled the recovery process, which began promisingly in 2000, generating a respectable 4.8 percent growth rate. \par \par \uc2  Predictably, barely three months into the 2001 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, official assumptions on key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators, including 5 percent gross domestic product growth, inflation of 7.2 percent, an average rupiah rate of 7,800 to the dollar and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate of 11.5 percent, were soon rendered irrelevant. \par \par \uc2  The government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  eventually agreed in June to revise the key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumptions to 3.5 percent GDP growth, an average exchange rate of 9,600 rupiah to the dollar, an average interest rate of 15 percent and a 9.3 percent inflation rate. \par \par \uc2  The GDP growth rate plunged from 5.2 percent in the last quarter of 2000 to a mere 1.81 percent in the first quarter of 2001, and slowed to 4 percent on a year-on-year basis. As market confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  worsened, the rupiah crashed to 31-month lows of more than Rp 11,500 to the dollar in April. \par \par \uc2  As the confrontation between then president Abdurrahman and the House grew more intense between April and June, with Abdurrahman resorting to threats, intimidation and political blackmail in a desperate bid to cling to power, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  entered what the World Bank described in January as a "muddle through" scenario. \par \par \uc2  The Central Bureau of Statistics came up with an even gloomier picture for the second quarter, putting GDP growth at 0.09 percent on a quarterly basis and at 3.52 percent on a yearly basis. \par \par \uc2  Muddle through was precisely what the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  did during the year. A modicum of macroeconomic stability was maintained, but \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hemorrhaging continued to weaken the recovery as most reform measures fell behind schedule. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook did not improve significantly even after the nation resolved its political crisis peacefully in late July by electing Megawati Soekarnoputri as the new president and Hamzah Has as her deputy. \par \par \uc2  The third quarter did record a higher growth rate of 2.38 percent on a quarterly basis and 3.47 percent on a yearly basis, thereby bringing the cumulative expansion during the first three quarters to 3.3 percent. This led to a great deal of optimism that annual growth would likely reach the revised projection of 3.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  But that growth was still far from the minimum 7 percent expansion needed to absorb the 2.5 to 3 million new job seekers who enter the market annually, not to mention the tens of millions already made jobless by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, with annual growth of between just 3.3 and 4 percent, the country may need six or seven years to return to the level it was at prior to 1997, given the 14 percent contraction in 1998, almost zero growth in 1999 and an expansion of 4.8 percent in 2000. \par \par \uc2  The hopes for a more rapid pace of reform that accompanied the election of the new president were soon dashed, even before the Megawati government passed the traditional honeymoon period of its first 100 days in office. \par \par \uc2  Despite her unanimous election by the People's Consultative Assembly, and even though her political party was the single largest faction in the House, her government failed to secure full \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  support for accelerating the reform program. \par \par \uc2  The new government did act quickly to mend ties with the IMF with the signing of a new reform agreement in August, followed in September by the third $400 million loan disbursement, which had been held up since January. \par \par \uc2  But the IMF's endorsement of the government's reform program failed to restore market confidence, as the core elements of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis management process remained bogged down in politics. \par \par \uc2  The House simply failed to comprehend the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  logic of a faster pace of asset recovery and privatization of state companies. It instead harbored a misguided nationalistic sentiment against foreign investors acquiring assets in the country, fearing that foreigners would come to dominate the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook became even gloomier after the Sept.11 terrorist attacks on the United States. The tragedy drove the American \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  deeper into recession and consequently further weakened global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions. \par \par \uc2  The country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was abruptly deprived of its main driver, the export market, which together with private consumption had become the engine of Indonesian growth last year. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, inordinately emotional anti-American street demonstrations in several cities in September and October projected such a horrifying image that Indonesia, for some time, appeared to the outside world to be a country controlled by radical Muslims. Even though the voice of reason eventually prevailed, the damage to Indonesia's image had already been done. \par \par \uc2  Obviously, not only Americans but also quite a number of other expatriates were scared away. Many importers in the U.S., Indonesia's single largest market, abruptly canceled orders, fearing delivery problems. \par \par \uc2  Sadly, too, many foreign buyers, who had played a vital role in helping Indonesian exporters gain a foothold in overseas markets, decided to cancel their regular visit programs. Consequently, Indonesian exports, which had began to decline in the first quarter due to the weakening of the U.S. and Japanese economies, suddenly plunged, falling by almost 17 percent in September alone. \par \par \uc2  Minister of Industry and Trade Rini Soewandi estimated early last month that the country would be lucky to record $42 billion in non-oil exports this year, compared to $47 billion last year. \par \par \uc2  The worsening levels of market confidence drove the rupiah down further, to almost 11,000 to the dollar in October and November. This exacerbated inflationary pressures, making it even more difficult for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and rendering the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment increasingly inimical to sound banking operations. \par \par \uc2  Significantly cutting \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid the severe depreciation of the rupiah, which was called for by many businesspeople and some analysts, would not only have jacked up inflation but would also have prompted a shift to dollar positions. \par \par \uc2  Even more worrisome were the government's severe cash-flow problems caused by lower than predicted revenue receipts and higher than budgeted \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs. \par \par \uc2  Actual revenues are likely to be well below the official target because asset sales, debt restructuring and privatization of state companies have been much slower than expected due to excessive interference from the House and adverse market conditions. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, foreign creditors have held up almost $1.7 billion of their $2.6 billion program loans pledged to the 2001 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the government's failure to significantly cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , combined with its low success rate in meeting reform commitments. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, actual \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  may overshoot the budgeted total because the rupiah rate has been much lower, and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  much higher, than the levels assumed by \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecasts. \par \par \uc2  Hence, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been deprived of sorely-needed investment as the private sector, burdened with bad debts, cannot provide the necessary \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while foreign investors remain jittery about the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , political and security conditions as well as its legal system. \par \par \uc2  The banking industry, which had been restructured and recapitalized at a total cost of about $65 billion, is still too weak to significantly expand corporate lending. \par \par \uc2  There is indeed a lot about the short and medium-term health of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that should be cause for concern, especially with the deadweight cost of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector's debt overhang, which has reached as much as 120 percent of GDP. \par \par \uc2  It will therefore be almost impossible for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow even by a mere 3 percent next year in the absence of a new rescheduling package for foreign debts maturing within the next three years and without speedier asset recovery, corporate debt restructuring and privatization of state companies. \par \par \uc2  Asset sales and privatization are now the most promising source of the new private capital flows that are needed to restore investor confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in view of the overcapacity present in almost all manufacturing industries. And foreign investment, at least over the next two to three years, will be the lifeblood of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  But many reform measures have simply failed to materialize, even under strong pressure from the IMF, World Bank and other foreign creditors, which tie their loans to \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform. \par \par \uc2  The greatest lesson the government should draw from this utterly inept performance is that a faster pace of reform is the key to a sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  However, reform can be sustained only by a strong consensus between the government and the House and not by the force of foreign aid or loans because reform requires changes in coalitions, in ideas and in interests. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011227dxcs00060\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
