\par\par \b \uc2  Local mining industry remains in the doldrums. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Moch. N. Kurniawan, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 1,004 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  17 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  In this first year of the implementation of regional autonomy, the country's mining industry remained in the doldrums. \par \par \uc2  The autonomy laws were, in the beginning, expected to solve security problems confronting mining companies since the downfall of former president Soeharto in mid-1998. \par \par \uc2  As it turned out, this year, mining operations continued facing problems, ranging from land disputes, labor strikes, illegal mining, blockades and lawsuits. \par \par \uc2  The autonomy laws - consisting of the Autonomy Law No. 22/1999, which gives greater freedom to local legislators to run their political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  affairs, and the Intergovernmental \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  Balance Law No. 25/1999, which allows the regions to gain greater benefits from the development of their natural resources - came into force on Jan. 1 2001. \par \par \uc2  The laws which at first were expected to become a solution have in fact created multi-faceted problems - in the sense that they have been used liberally as an excuse for many locals to pressure mining investors to meet their demands. \par \par \uc2  Among companies facing such problems this year are coal mining company PT Arutmin Indonesia in South Kalimantan, PT Kaltim Prima Coal (KPC) in East Kalimantan, gold mining firm Kelian Equatorial Mining (KEM) in East Kalimantan and state tin mining firm PT Timah Tbk. \par \par \uc2  Illegal miners have for a long time been causing trouble for Arutmin's operation in Kotabaru regency. When the police moved to stop them by confiscating their mining equipment in the middle of the year, the illegal miners staged protests and forced the police to return the equipment. \par \par \uc2  Arutmin produces 8.7 million tons of coal a year. \par \par \uc2  KEM has also been complaining about the troubles caused by illegal miners on its operation in West Kutai regency. \par \par \uc2  Last year, the illegal miners mostly harassed foreign mining operations, while most of the operations of the state mining companies remained relatively safe. \par \par \uc2  But, in this gloomy year, Timah, which was considered the world's most efficient tin mining company and touted as a model for all the country's state companies, has been pushed to the brink of bankruptcy due to the illegal miners. \par \par \uc2  The illegal miners which operate around Timah's operation on Bangka and Belitung islands in the Sumatra Straits have not only paralyzed Timah but also pushed down the world's tin price by flooding the market with cheap tin. \par \par \uc2  The government has actually set up a special team to handle the illegal miners but the team has yet to prove its effectiveness. \par \par \uc2  KPC, a joint venture of Anglo-Australian Rio Tinto and Anglo-American energy firm BP Plc. which produces 15 million tons of coal per year in Sangatta, East Kalimantan, is facing a different problem. \par \par \uc2  It has been constantly under pressure from the East Kalimantan administration to sell its 51 percent stake to a joint venture partly owned by the administration at the price set by the administration, which is lower than the price set by the company. \par \par \uc2  Under the contract signed in the 1980s, KPC is obligated to sell a 51 percent stake to the Indonesian government, state companies, Indonesians-controlled private companies or Indonesian citizens after ten years of operation. \par \par \uc2  In its latest pressure bid, the provincial administration recently filed a lawsuit against the company at the South Jakarta District Court on charges of intentionally delaying the divestment program. \par \par \uc2  In addition to harassment, blockage and lawsuits, many mining companies had to deal with the local governments imposing new levies and \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on them in a bid to boost revenue. \par \par \uc2  This is actually a breach of the legal contracts signed with the central government, but in most cases, the central government, from which the investors asked for help, looks impotent to force the regions to revoke the \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Firdaus Asikin, an analyst at PriceWaterhouseCoopers said all these problems had further deteriorated the country's mining investment climate, which has been hurt by the prolonged social and political turmoils. \par \par \uc2  He warned no new mining investors would be willing to come to Indonesia in the coming years, if the government couldn't cope with the problem. \par \par \uc2  Indeed, many mining companies have suspended their operations due to the security problems, while new investors have delayed their investment plans. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Mining Association's executive director P.L Coutrier said it was too early to conclude that the government's autonomy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had aggravated the mining industry's problems as the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been in place for only a year. \par \par \uc2  "The autonomy is a good concept. That many problems remain, it is because it is just one year old," he told the Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  He was optimistic that in the long run, problems now confronting the mining industry would be solved thanks to the autonomy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  All stakeholders should work together to make a success out of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rather than blaming each other, he said. \par \par \uc2  Director general of geology and mineral resources at the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources Wimpy S. Tjetjep agreed that the autonomy \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was a good concept. \par \par \uc2  "The main problems are legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security concerns," Wimpy said. \par \par \uc2  Some people may say the autonomy laws were good enough, but the government has decided to review them. \par \par \uc2  In order to end the chaotic situation in the mining industry, the government has planned to introduce a new law to replace the existing Mining Law of 1967, which is considered too centralistic, thus no longer suitable to the spirit of autonomy. \par \par \uc2  According to Wimpy, the government will submit the new mining bill to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  early next year. \par \par \uc2  The new law would ensure the regional governments's authority over the mining sector, a legal certainty over the existing contract of work, and give no discrimination for new local and foreign investors, Wimpy said. \par \par \uc2  The new law is thus expected to give a stronger legal foundation for the regions to benefit from their mining resources and for investors to gain protection for their investment. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011228dxcs0000k\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Consumer confidence down. \b0\par\par\uc2 298 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 December 2001\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The index of consumer confidence has gone down, as the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  expressed its pessimism over the weak coordination among Cabinet members on legal and security issues said the Danareksa Riset Institute in a press release issued yesterday. \par \par \uc2  "Compared to October, the index dropped from 107.7 to 105.6," the DRI statement. \par \par \uc2  The new figure reflected a slower growth from 87.7 to 89.5. \par \par \uc2  The study also showed the index of expectation that dropped by 4.1%, from 122.8 to 117.7, as consumers show little optimism over \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  The index on confidence in the government also dropped, from 134.0 to 132.7, caused by what they see as weak coordination among Cabinet members. \par \par \uc2  DRI said the index dropped due to the government's inability to boost the people's purchasing power and the excessive expectation of the ministers' ability to deal with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, "as the challenges fluctuate." \par \par \uc2  Consumer confidence is a decisive factor as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rests on domestic consumption. \par \par \uc2  Senior \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti this week said that since 1998/99 the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew positively albeit with a dismal figure of only 3.2%-3.5%. \par \par \uc2  The study also showed that consumers are now more realistic in forming their opinion on the Cabinet. \par \par \uc2  Danareksa said consumer sentiment toward the government dropped because security personnel failed to anticipate threats against foreigners here. \par \par \uc2  This \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation could weaken the prospects of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and spark inflation, as demand for US$ rises for speculative purposes that would undermine the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The Cabinet must share a common vision, which is to boost the people's purchasing power by seeing the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grow and by stabilizing prices. \par \par \uc2  This could only be achieved if the situation is marked by law and order. (aph). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020011231dxct0005n\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4