\par\par \b \uc2  It's not (only) the  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 , stupid. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,259 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  18 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Economics is extremely useful as a form of employment for economists. \par \par \uc2  In economics, the majority is always wrong \par \par \uc2  - John Kenneth Galbraith \par \par \uc2  Few people today will argue that a part, probably a large part if not the entire part, of the problem with the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  today lies with noneconomic factors. Even most economists, in their search for explanations for what has gone wrong with our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies - and therefore the theories underpinning the policies they advocate - would quickly find faults in what they call the noneconomic factors. \par \par \uc2  How much weight do they attribute to these factors for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  failures is the subject of a debate. This much was clear at a recent panel discussion hosted by The Jakarta Post to look into the prospects of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2002. \par \par \uc2  At one end of the debate, there are those who feel there is something fundamentally very wrong with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system that Indonesia has been building these last three or four decades. \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makers, they argue, have blindly relied on neoclassical \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theories, which essentially advocate market forces as the best determinant for the most efficient allocation of scarce \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resources. This has been going on since the time of President Soeharto until today. \par \par \uc2  These proponents argue that instead of correcting Soeharto's mistakes, the current "reformist" regime is continuing the trend, prescribing even more \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  liberalization measures as Indonesia's only \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  salvation. \par \par \uc2  To "institutional economists", as these groups of economists are often referred to in the study of the dismal science, the problem with Indonesia lies not with its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, but with the entire system. Their prescription to cure Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ills is therefore a complete overhaul of the system. \par \par \uc2  In drawing up a new system, the government must incorporate other social science disciplines, including cultural factors. In short, they are saying that the neoclassical \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theories, upon which most of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies of Indonesia today are founded, are flawed because they are imported wholly from the West without adapting them to local conditions. \par \par \uc2  The speaker in the panel discussion who advocated this, however, fell short of calling for a total revolution, but that is what it essentially boils down to. If he is not advocating a physical revolution, he is certainly advocating a radical change in our approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems. \par \par \uc2  But the concept of building a system that relies less on market forces and more on institutional elements, including on the national Pancasila ideology to guide policies and on a greater government role, smacks of socialism, whose \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theories and system have been widely discarded as largely ineffective. \par \par \uc2  The success of the "people's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 " these last two years is often cited as the chief reason why Indonesia should search for an alternative and more indigenous \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system. It is argued that the traditional sector has been Indonesia's salvation these last two years, fueling \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and creating jobs to cushion ordinary people from the impact of the crisis while the modern \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector has been struggling to free itself from mountains of unpaid debts. \par \par \uc2  "Since the big ship of Indonesia has been saved by the people's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is no more reason to keep denying the existence and role of the people's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As this sector has proven its independence from foreign capital, there is no more reason to think that foreign investment is an absolute necessity," a proponent of the institutional \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  approach says. \par \par \uc2  At the other end of the debate are those economists who advocate less radical, though not necessarily less drastic, changes in approach to our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems, believing that at the end of the day, supply and demand market forces are still the best mechanisms to ensure \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  efficiency, and even, with the right kind of policies, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fairness. \par \par \uc2  These economists argue that Soeharto's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies of the last three decades were in fact much closer to the communist system than to one based on free market forces. The granting of monopolistic rights and constant government intervention in the market has rendered the theory of free market forces inoperative all this time, they argue. \par \par \uc2  They too find many faults in noneconomic factors, but only to the extent of disrupting the market mechanism. Legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security disturbances, for example, have plagued Indonesia particularly in these last three years since Soeharto's downfall, so much so that investors would think twice before committing their money in this country. And then, there is the perennial problem of corruption, which in Indonesia goes hand in hand with the ineffective, if not inept, bureaucracy. \par \par \uc2  But it would be a fallacy to pin the blame solely on corruption for Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  failings, even if Indonesia is regarded as one of the most corrupt nations in the world. How then do you explain Indonesia's rapid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rates of the 1980s and 1990s, when Indonesia was not less corrupt than it is today. And how do you explain the high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rates of China and Vietnam, which, while not as corrupt, are corrupt nevertheless? \par \par \uc2  But while corruption did not trigger Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis in 1997, it certainly made the situation worse, one economist argues. Today, Indonesia's inability to lift itself out of its present predicament could, to a large extent, be explained by the continuing rampant corruption at almost every level in government. \par \par \uc2  Any attempt to explain Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems must take into account these various noneconomic factors. Whether these factors render \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theories invalid is another matter. \par \par \uc2  Some economists try to explain this in terms of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  theory of imperfect competition, by including various noneconomic factors as variables in their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  models. They were at least able to deduce that part of our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  problems lie not with the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself, but with these other variables. \par \par \uc2  While no \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the world can ever reach the ideal of a perfect market, this approach also allows economists to identify problems and their solutions. In the case of Indonesia, some of these problems have now been addressed; whether they are effective or not is another question. The government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , for example, enacted the antimonopoly law this year. With reform continuing to be the mantra of the present regime, perhaps things will improve over time. \par \par \uc2  One economist at the panel discussion argues that the most important \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform for Indonesia should be in the real \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, particularly in the trade and industrial sectors, rather than in the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary sectors. \par \par \uc2  "The trade and industrial sectors are the ones that create the jobs, growth and everything else. \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies can provide the necessary conducive atmosphere," argues the panelist. On this front, Indonesia still has plenty of homework to do. \par \par \uc2  In conclusion, while economists seem to agree that noneconomic factors have played a major role in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance all these years - or the lack of it - they have different prescriptions for the cure. One camp suggests a complete overhaul of the system, while another suggests \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, which are no less drastic. \par \par \uc2  The jury will probably be forever out on this question, because today, this is still largely an academic debate which boils down to how fast and how drastically should we implement reforms. Right now, those advocating gradual reforms seem to have the upper hand, but let's not rule out the alternative, that of a complete overhaul, even if only as an academic exercise. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011230dxcv00062\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
