\par\par \b \uc2  Government's  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal \highlight\uc2  responsibility a faint hope. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,162 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  16 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  There is no way to paint a bright picture illustrating Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for 2002. Too many lingering problems remain that will haunt next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Huge debt repayment, a continued high level of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  (especially fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) and increased funding for regencies eat up most budgetary \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, regarding income, problems are noticeable on the potential for dwindling revenues from falling crude oil prices coupled with the expected slower pace of privatization and sale of assets. \par \par \uc2  The 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , approved by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Oct. 25, targets a total state revenue of Rp 301.9 trillion (about US$30 billion) and foresees state expenditures of Rp 344 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  for next year will be Rp 42.1 trillion - or equal to 2.5 percent of the country's Gross Domestic Product (GDP). \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  could grow bigger since some elements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially foreign debt servicing, are not yet finalized. \par \par \uc2  According to World Bank projections, the government's foreign debt, due next year, totals US$15.5 billion in principal and another $5.4 billion in interest payments. \par \par \uc2  Out of those amounts, the government allocates for the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  only Rp 41.5 trillion (about 4.5 billion) to pay amortization of foreign debt, and another Rp 27.4 trillion for interest. \par \par \uc2  It is expected that the remaining debt principal and interests would be rescheduled through the Paris Club of creditors. \par \par \uc2  Judging by Indonesia's success in rescheduling US$5.8 billion in foreign debt principle that was due this year, the government is confident it will get further rescheduling from its creditors - for both the principal and interest on its foreign debt for the 2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  year. \par \par \uc2  But even if the government manages to get secure rescheduling of its debt as it wants, the problem on foreign debt servicing does not stop here. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's volatile exchange rate against the U.S. dollar adds \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for year 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as this will affect the government's foreign debt servicing. \par \par \uc2  The 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumes an average rupiah exchange rate of 9,000 against the U.S. dollar, while in reality, the rupiah is now traded in the market at over Rp 10,000 per U.S. dollar. \par \par \uc2  If the rupiah remains weak at over Rp 10,000, foreign debt servicing will increase by at least 10 percent from that allocated in the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Weak rupiah would also eventually affect the government's interest payments on its mounting domestic debt. \par \par \uc2  If the rupiah continues to struggle next year, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  would stay high, adding burden to government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , as much of its domestic debt is tied to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  benchmark rates. \par \par \uc2  The 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumes that benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes average at 14 percent annually, while current benchmark rates stay above 17 percent. \par \par \uc2  According to data at the Finance Ministry, government bonds will mature in 2002 total by Rp 11.56 trillion, compared to Rp 8.8 trillion this year. \par \par \uc2  For this domestic debt, the government plans to re-finance some of them that fall due next year, by issuing new bonds totaling Rp 3.93 trillion. \par \par \uc2  In addition, next year, the government plans to repay some expensive domestic debts using proceeds from privatization of state companies and sales of assets pledged by failed debtors in exchange for their debts. \par \par \uc2  The proceeds that target the privatization program for next year are set at Rp 6.5 trillion, while the sale of assets under the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) is expected to rake in some Rp 48.2 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Of those amounts, some 25.7 trillion would be used to repay the domestic debt. \par \par \uc2  On top of that, the government has also to cash out Rp 59.6 trillion for interest payment. And this amount could increase again, depending on the level of benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Therefore, making the rupiah stronger against the dollar next year would save much for government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  in terms of foreign and domestic debt servicing. \par \par \uc2  Pursuing longer-term stability and strength of the rupiah would help the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden very much, due to its mounting foreign and domestic debt. \par \par \uc2  Currently, the government is shackled by its huge foreign debt of $72 billion and domestic debt of $60 billion, and this will continue to saddle state budgets for a long run. \par \par \uc2  Unlike foreign debt, which has been accumulated mostly over the past 35 years, the huge \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  domestic debt has arisen only in the past three years as a result of the government's decision to bail out banks and their owners. \par \par \uc2  Both foreign debts and domestic debts would continue to constrain \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, as the government has not enough revenue streams to repay those debts. \par \par \uc2  Domestic revenue streams for next year are also in question if they could meet the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  target of Rp 344 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Revenues from the oil and gas sector, which are projected to reach Rp 99 trillion this year, will drop 26 percent to Rp 73 trillion next year, assuming that crude oil price would drop to $22 per barrel. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, international crude oil prices are currently dropping below $20 per barrel, adding more concerns over the government's revenue from oil and gas. \par \par \uc2  To counter this, increasing non-oil \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues would become the only viable alternative to maintain the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  at 2.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  The government has targeted to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues from mostly non-oil income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT), respectively at Rp 88.8 trillion and Rp 70 trillion, a sharp increase from Rp 69 trillion and Rp 53 trillion. \par \par \uc2  However, slapping the increase on the income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and VAT is a risky business, as it would affect businesses and consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The high rate of income \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on business would eventually affect business activities and higher VAT targets - the easiest way to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue - and would discourage consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  And this would eventually affect \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, rather than seeking the easiest way to get bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns from VAT and bigger income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  from existing taxpayers, the government should broaden its \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  base, by way of making more people pay \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  as they should. \par \par \uc2  According to the government data, only one million of the country's 220 million people have their own personal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  identification numbers. Worse still, only half actually file their annual income \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials estimate the potential number of eligible \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  payers exceeds 20 million people. Therefore, if the government spends more money to target these people, it would be able to finance its \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  without borrowing more money from foreign creditors. \par \par \uc2  However, if the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation stays like it is now - with a low \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection rate and a high level of foreign and domestic debt - the government will be destined to continue borrowing money to plug \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011231dxcv0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
