\par\par \b \uc2  Firmer measures needed to consolidate banks. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,083 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  17 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The panel of economists urged the government to take firmer measures against banks still failing to meet the minimum prudential standards set by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , otherwise the whole banking industry would remain highly vulnerable to shocks. \par \par \uc2  "The banks have been cleaned up of their bad assets and recapitalized, and their losses have been transferred to the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, yet they are still unable to resume proper financial intermediation," one panelist noted. \par \par \uc2  What the panelist was referring to was the fact that the government had recapitalized all state banks and seven major private banks, reimbursed depositors and creditors of closed banks and taken over bad loans from banks at a total cost of around Rp 650 trillion (US$65 billion). \par \par \uc2  The government covered the huge cost by issuing bonds that cost taxpayers almost Rp 60 trillion in interest charges annually. \par \par \uc2  Another panelist asserted that it would be better to close weak banks now than continue to support them at the risk of threatening the whole banking industry. \par \par \uc2  Closure, he added, would involve \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  up front but would reduce costs over the medium term and at the same time generate market confidence in the whole industry. \par \par \uc2  Further delays and indecisiveness would only increase the contingent liabilities of the government with regard to the banking industry, especially now that the government already owns more than 70 percent of the banking industry as a result of massive recapitalization in 1999 and 2000. \par \par \uc2  Further delays would only postpone another, bigger banking crisis, which the government certainly could not cope with, since the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector itself is already on the verge of default under a mountain of foreign and domestic debts. \par \par \uc2  Though the massive restructuring decreased the number of domestic banks from 178 in 1997 to 120 at present, it is considered still too many for the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to supervise. While most other countries have raised the capital standards of their banks to a minimum 12 percent, the capital adequacy ratio (CAR) of most Indonesian banks is only 8 percent, the minimum level set by Switzerland's Bank for International Settlement (Basle). \par \par \uc2  Given the highly risky business environment in the country and the lenient asset classification applied to banks, the minimum CAR for Indonesian banks should at least be 15 percent to provide a stronger cushion for shocks. \par \par \uc2  Most major banks, notably those recapitalized in 1999 and 2000, have been awash in liquidity but they still hesitate to resume corporate lending, apparently due to the high risks of eroding their capital standard. \par \par \uc2  Data at the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  shows that bank loans outstanding as of August totaled only Rp 287.8 trillion, compared to Rp 734 trillion third-party deposits raised by banks. This means a lending-to-deposit ratio of less than 40 percent. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, nonperforming loans, though down from 36.14 percent in June 2000, to 20.60 percent in December 2000, remained relatively high at 15.50 percent as of September, still much higher than the minimum percent required by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Lack of significant progress in corporate debt restructuring, fragile \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and continued \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  seem to have forced banks to opt first for safety by investing the bulk of their funds in \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes or lending to the interbank market. \par \par \uc2  As the CAR (the ratio between capital and risk-weighted assets) of many major banks remain close to the minimum 8 percent and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition is worsening amid the gloomier outlook of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the United States, banks have been extra careful about new major lending. \par \par \uc2  The persistently tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  imposed by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cope with strong inflationary pressures caused by the weakening rupiah has made things even much tougher for commercial bank operations, with their costs of funds often higher than their lending revenues. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, as the assets of the recapitalized banks are dominated by government bonds, which are rather illiquid due to an undeveloped secondary market, many banks are not really as highly liquid as widely assumed because they cannot easily convert their bonds to cash. \par \par \uc2  Without a significant increase in new lending, most banks will remain highly vulnerable to shocks since domestic banks, unlike foreign banks which have developed a significant source of fee-based incomes, still depend mainly on net interest margin for their incomes. \par \par \uc2  However, the pace of corporate lending will be determined by the performance of the business sector. As long as most medium and large business conglomerates remain in the care of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA), being treated for their huge bad debts, banks will find it difficult to get viable borrowers. \par \par \uc2  The panelists sharply criticized the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's persistently tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , arguing that since the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector cannot provide any \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  should substantially ease the money supply to fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities. \par \par \uc2  They found it hard to comprehend the rationale behind the credit crunch at a time when most businesses are in bad need of credit financing and most other countries have sharply cut their \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The tight monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  makes the environment inimical for the restructured banks to expand lending operations. \par \par \uc2  The government would be well advised to sell as quickly as possible most of the banks it now wholly owns or in which it has a majority stake to new investors to speed up their operational restructuring. \par \par \uc2  Without operational restructuring - the rationalization of branches and staffing level, improvements in credit practices, risk management and internal governance - the banks will never regain \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence and will therefore continue to depend on the government blanket guarantee, under which the government has guaranteed all depositors' money. \par \par \uc2  People are still willing to keep their money at domestic banks mainly because of the government guarantee. But even with the support of this guarantee, domestic banks are still perceived to be highly risky, as reflected in the much higher deposit \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  they have to offer to attract depositors, compared to those given by foreign banks. \par \par \uc2  But the blanket guarantee is only an emergency measure that is supposed to be terminated within one or two years to allow the market forces to screen out structurally weak banks. \par \par \uc2  It is nonetheless widely expected that the pressures on the rupiah will decline next year as political stability takes deeper root. A stable and stronger rupiah will decrease inflationary pressures, thereby enabling the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  to relax its credit crunch. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011231dxcv0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
