\par\par \b \uc2  Privatization should be reactivated. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,017 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 December 2001\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  18 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2001 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The panelists agreed that privatization of state-owned enterprises (SOEs), like asset sales by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency, were capable of reinvigorating the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Divestment would bring in additional revenue to the cash-strapped government to enable it to reduce its debt burden, and improve investor confidence in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as investors would improve the efficiency of SOEs. \par \par \uc2  Privatization was greatly effective in improving macroeconomic efficiency through the creation of a more competitive market. And its microeconomic benefits were equally far-reaching, including more efficient and consequently more profitable enterprises, a significant increase in investment, a broader technological base and managerial depth and better products at lower costs to consumers. \par \par \uc2  However, privatization appeared a dirty word, political ammunition that was often fired by vested interest groups to incite people to demonstrate and provoke employees to strike, as the Semen Gresik debacle over the last few months had shown. \par \par \uc2  One panelist asserted that without a faster pace of privatization, the cash-starved government, already burdened with mountains of debts, would have to depend on new borrowings to finance its \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Worse still, he added, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would continue to suffer from inefficiencies because the more than 180 SOEs that provided \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  services, produce industrial materials and operate in such vital sectors as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  utilities and banking, were notorious for corruption and collusive dealings. \par \par \uc2  "Moreover, we are now like a communist country where the government owns, controls or manages almost 80 percent of productive assets," he pointed out. \par \par \uc2  He referred to the thousands of assets consisting of enterprises, banks and equity stakes in companies which were taken over by the government after the restructuring of the banking industry in 1997-2000. \par \par \uc2  "These assets have to be unleashed to private investors as soon as possible, otherwise their quality will continue to decline," he added. \par \par \uc2  The government itself acknowledged in its latest letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on Dec. 13, that privatization of state-owned enterprises (SOEs) was a key part of its reform efforts aimed at improving \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance and strengthening the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector's finances. \par \par \uc2  It also admitted that SOEs had often been inefficient providers of goods and services, a drain on the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  finances and exploited as cash cows for the benefits of individuals and special-interest groups. \par \par \uc2  Just look at the findings of independent audits on SOEs, which were made at the request of the IMF as part of the reform program. \par \par \uc2  The second round of independent audits that involved five SOEs - PT Pelabuhan Indonesia port company, PT Jasa Marga toll road operator, PT Perkebunan Nusantara IV plantation company, PT Garuda Indonesia national flag carrier and PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia (Telkom) - showed how grossly inefficient SOEs were. \par \par \uc2  The audits discovered Rp 8.5 trillion or $1.6 billion in losses due to inefficiency, Rp 7.3 trillion in potential losses from shady or questionable deals and Rp 776 billion or $147 million in lost opportunities for gains or savings. \par \par \uc2  Given their large size in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the SOEs weak performance has acted as a major drag on the overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance. \par \par \uc2  The government therefore has reiterated its commitment to speed up privatization. \par \par \uc2  The government has indeed failed miserably in its privatization program since 1998. It had set 12 SOEs for divestment each year since 1998 but has so far divested only around five, because almost every deal was embroiled in political controversy and allegations of corruption. \par \par \uc2  Not a single cent of the Rp 6.5 trillion in revenues expected from privatization was collected in 2000. This year, only Rp 3.5 trillion of the Rp 6.5 trillion revenue target was achieved. Even these revenues were made only through a further divestment in listed PT Telkom, which was privatized in 1995. \par \par \uc2  No one disagrees that privatization was fundamentally a political transformation and a difficult task as it exacted a major change in the government's role in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  against the strong opposition from vested interest groups. \par \par \uc2  Vested interest groups, including many politicians in the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , whipped up xenophobia in their attempts to block privatization, arguing that the measure amounts to the surrender of national sovereignty to foreigners. \par \par \uc2  Other opponents of the program have warned the government against selling SOEs at cheap prices under the current adverse conditions, arguing that asset prices will eventually rise when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  strengthens. \par \par \uc2  The problem though is that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not likely gain a sustainable recovery unless many major SOEs are released to private investors who were certainly better managers than the government. \par \par \uc2  As one panelist pointed out: "You cannot have the cake and eat it too." \par \par \uc2  He said asset prices would increase only if the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  regained investor confidence, but this confidence would never be won unless the government showed a good \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance regarding privatization. \par \par \uc2  Obviously, selling state companies now would not fetch the best prices, given the high risks associated with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about law enforcement and the initial complications from decentralization of political and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  autonomy to provinces and districts. \par \par \uc2  It was completely irrational to predict what is possible from transactions done in the best of times compared to those conducted in the worst of times we are in now, especially in view of the bleak outlook of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the United States, the world's biggest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  powerhouse. \par \par \uc2  As the case for faster privatization is so compelling, seen from \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability and macroeconomic efficiency, many had found it hard to understand why the government had not yet formulated a broad legal and political framework for the program and set clear-cut guidelines for privatization transactions. \par \par \uc2  The World Bank suggested in its latest report on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that the government reach a broad consensus with the House on SOE restructuring and a privatization strategy on which individual transactions would be based. \par \par \uc2  But given the bitter experiences in past privatization efforts, the government also needed to formulate standard operational procedures, the step-by-step process for divestment in SOEs to secure transparency and accountability. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2001 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020011231dxcv0000n\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Prospect of BI-40 index in 2002 remains  \highlight22\uc2 uncertain \highlight\uc2 . \b0\par\par\uc2 178 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 January 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA: The investment prospect of Bisnis shares in 2002 remains \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Domestic political and security instabilities are likely to remain \par \par \uc2  dominant \par \par \uc2  over the transaction activities. \par \par \uc2  In the meantime, the slow \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery would also hamper the share \par \par \uc2  movements to a higher level. Investment challenges in 2002 is also \par \par \uc2  predicted \par \par \uc2  to come from outside, mostly an inevitable threat of global recession. \par \par \uc2  The \par \par \uc2  US \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's efforts to lower the \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  of up to 4 times \par \par \uc2  post \par \par \uc2  the WTC attacks have failed to show significant impact on the world's \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Such reality indicated that the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospect in 2002 \par \par \uc2  remains \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This also means that investment prospect in Indonesia's \par \par \uc2  capital \par \par \uc2  market is bleak. Investors would continue to watch any improvements \par \par \uc2  within \par \par \uc2  the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and would place long terms investments only on good \par \par \uc2  signs. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand