\par\par \b \uc2  Military to get new mandate to crush GAM. \b0\par\par\uc2 630 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 February 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Annastashya Emmanuelle and Fabiola Desy Unidjaja, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The government, which has come under strong criticism from human rights activists for reviving the Aceh military command just this week, is now set to give a new mandate to the military to crush the separatist movement in Aceh. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for Political, Social and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono said on Thursday that President Megawati Soekarnoputri would soon issue a Presidential Instruction maintaining the current security approach against the armed wing of the Free Aceh Movement (GAM). \par \par \uc2  "Any separatist movement must be crushed, and we have the international support to maintain our national territorial integrity," Susilo said after a limited cabinet meeting at the State Secretariat on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Susilo's announcement came just days after the Indonesian military revived the Iskandar Muda Military Command in Aceh despite strong protest from human rights activist and Acehnese people for fear of more rights abuse in the province. \par \par \uc2  It reflects the government's preference to resolve the Aceh question militarily, as opposed to diplomacy, which was pursued by former president Abdurrahman Wahid. \par \par \uc2  This is also against the military's own pledge to phase out its territorial role, which has long been criticized for having hindered the development of democracy. \par \par \uc2  With its territorial function, the military has been deeply involved in civil affairs, especially during the administration of former president Soeharto, who used military networks down to the village level to silence its critics. \par \par \uc2  Resolving the Aceh question through military action is expected to worsen human rights abuses in the province, where more than 1,700 people were killed in 2001 and at least 200 people have already died in 2002. \par \par \uc2  Susilo also expressed the government's reluctance to pursue talks with GAM, saying that the separatist movement remained unclear whether they would accept the autonomy package or not. \par \par \uc2  "Should the dialog continue to proceed in an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  manner, while there isn't a sincere indication from GAM to find a peaceful solution to the Aceh question, the government might later decide to stop the dialog," Susilo said. \par \par \uc2  The government and GAM met in Geneva, Switzerland last week to find a peaceful and comprehensive solution to the armed struggle in Aceh. No substantial agreement was reached in the two-day meeting. \par \par \uc2  Susilo said President Megawati would sign a Presidential Instruction early next week that would be effective for six months only. The new ruling replaces the current Presidential Instruction No. 7/2001, which was issued by former president Abdurrahman Wahid in April 2001, and is set to expire on Feb. 11. \par \par \uc2  The Presidential Instruction No.7/2001 has, as its focus, the restoration of law and order in Aceh. The instruction provides necessary legal grounds for military personnel to target armed civilians, particularly GAM members and independence fighters. \par \par \uc2  "The main pillar of the new Presidential Instruction is the Nanggroe Aceh Darusalam Autonomy Law," said Susilo, adding that the government was trying to introduce a comprehensive solution to the Aceh question. \par \par \uc2  "The comprehensive measures will cover socio-political, legal and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  approaches to the Aceh issue, and will be carried out by the central and provincial governments," he said without elaborating. \par \par \uc2  According to Susilo, with the implementation of the Autonomy Law, the Aceh governor and his administration would bear the responsibility of taking necessary steps to restore peace and order in the restive province. \par \par \uc2  "The central government's role is only to provide support, except for functions which were not included in the Autonomy Law, such as foreign relations and defense," he said. \par \par \uc2  Susilo also dismissed skepticism over the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to adopt a militaristic approach to solve security problems in Aceh, adding that any separatist movement should be crushed. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020208dy280000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
