\par\par \b \uc2  Govt aims to cut down debt ratio to 60%. \b0\par\par\uc2 655 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 February 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The government said on Monday it aimed to lower the country's debt-to-gross domestic product (GDP) ratio to 60 percent by 2004 from about 83 percent currently, hoping to lift a massive burden from the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  It said Indonesia's total debt to the end of December this year would remain at US$129.7 billion, as against $139 billion as of April last year. \par \par \uc2  A debt of $129.7 billion at an exchange rate of Rp 10,400 to the U.S. dollar translates to an 83 percent debt-to-GDP ratio. That is assuming a GDP of Rp 1,688 trillion (about $160 billion), which the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  targets for this year. \par \par \uc2  GDP is the total value of goods and services produced in a country during a specific period. \par \par \uc2  Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti said the country's sovereign debt stood at $71.4 billion to the end of Decmber 2002. \par \par \uc2  Of that amount, $58.3 billion was the government's, and the remaining $13.1 billion belonged to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said. \par \par \uc2  Domestic debt, which consisted of government bonds injected into local banks, amounted to Rp 606 trillion, he said. \par \par \uc2  "The government's foreign debt management \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  focuses on lowering the debt-to-GDP ratio to 60 percent by the year 2004," he said in a statement. \par \par \uc2  By 2004, the government hopes to achieve a balanced state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is suffering from a chronic \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The single largest contributor to the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  by far remains government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on debt repayments. \par \par \uc2  This year alone, the allocation for debt repayment hits Rp 136.l9 trillion, or a hefty 40 percent of the entire budgetary \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  As a consequence of such budgetary constraints, there is little room left for crucial development \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which spurs \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  But despite the government's limited capacity to boost the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Dorodjatun said it would achieve the lower debt-to-GDP ratio through \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  Speaking after a Cabinet meeting, he explained that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth increased Indonesia's debt payment capacity. \par \par \uc2  The 2002 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumes an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate of 4 percent, from around 3.5 percent last year. \par \par \uc2  But while the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could expect little from the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it may also not get the same boost it did last year from other \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  key drivers. \par \par \uc2  Fueling last year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mainly was robust domestic consumption, and Dorodjatun admitted Indonesia could not rely too much on that now. \par \par \uc2  Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , some analysts believed, could tail off this year on inflationary pressure and a lack of revenue growth. \par \par \uc2  The outlook on other key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  drivers remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Both investment and exports have fallen sharply on the double impact of Indonesia's adverse investment climate and a downturn in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Whether or not foreign investors are willing to return hinges much on the government's resolve to dispose of its assets amid strong antiforeign sentiment. \par \par \uc2  On exports, there is some hope of a turnaround in the global market later this year. But chances are slim that the rebound will be soon enough to push export sales out of their current slump. \par \par \uc2  Dorodjatun said that some foreign institutions had already raised doubts on Indonesia's ability to serve its debts. \par \par \uc2  "They (foreigners) have expressed some concern on our payment capacity," he said without elaborating the foreigners' concerns. \par \par \uc2  He added Indonesia's foreign debts, which consisted mainly of soft loans, were far more manageable compared with its domestic ones. \par \par \uc2  Most of the Rp 606 trillion in domestic debt is owed to local banks, which the government bailed out from the impact of the 1997 financial crisis by injecting with government bonds. \par \par \uc2  Unlike the foreign debts, the government is unlikely to restructure these bonds for fear it would destabilize the fragile banking industry. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020218dy2c000h7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
