\par\par \b \uc2  RI textile exports set to increase. \b0\par\par\uc2 510 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Textile Association (API) said on Wednesday that export revenue from textiles this year would increase to US$8 billion from $7.6 billion last year. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the Indonesian Footwear Association (Aprisindo) said the country's shoe exports would drop slightly by 6.25 percent to $1.5 billion this year, as some overseas buyers had begun turning their orders to other countries such as China and Vietnam, which offer lower prices. \par \par \uc2  API executive director Indra Ibrahim attributed the projected rise in textile exports to "aggressive marketing efforts" from producers, better government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the recovery of the U.S \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the second half of this year. He did not elaborate. \par \par \uc2  U.S. is Indonesia's largest export destination. \par \par \uc2  "With all these conditions, I'm quite optimistic the country's textile exports will recover this year," he was quoted by Antara as saying. \par \par \uc2  API said that the domestic textile industry had been hit by various \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  last year, including the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. \par \par \uc2  The association said riots and labor strikes at home had triggered foreign buyers to delay their orders, while several buyers shifted their orders to other countries. \par \par \uc2  Government policies had also been seen as discouraging, particularly on the government decision to raise fuel prices, electricity rates and the minimum wage. \par \par \uc2  API said that many textile companies had also not been able to renew their old machinery due the lack of working capital. \par \par \uc2  At the same time, demand from buyers has been sluggish following the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, which was worsened by the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks on the U.S. \par \par \uc2  The $7.6 billion textile exports in 2001 was a drop from $8.2 billion in 2000. \par \par \uc2  Separately, Aprisindo chairman Harijanto said overseas shoe buyers, particularly from the U.S., had begun shifting their orders to China and Vietnam due to the non-conducive business situation at home. \par \par \uc2  He added the entry of China to the World Trade Organization (WTO) had boosted China's competitiveness, but caused Indonesian products to become less competitive. \par \par \uc2  "Our products are now 12 percent more expensive than those from China and 20 percent higher in price than those from Vietnam," he said at a hearing session with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission V on industry and trade affairs. \par \par \uc2  Hariyanto said that the shoe industry had also been badly affected by the increase in fuel prices, electricity rates and minimum wage. \par \par \uc2  "If the government doesn't issue favorable polices for the sector, I'm certain that exports will decline and many companies will have to shut their factories down in the next three to four years." \par \par \uc2  He feared that many foreign investors in the sector would soon relocate their factories to China and Vietnam. \par \par \uc2  He also said that the government should accelerate the restructuring of debts owed by shoe companies to allow them to seek bank loans for working capital. \par \par \uc2  The country's shoe exports reached $1.6 billion last year and $2 billion in 2000. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020221dy2l00062\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Presidential decree bill on UKM's debt proposed - 50% discount for cash payers. \b0\par\par\uc2 864 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 February 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  State Minister of Cooperatives and Small-Middle Corporations Alimarwan Hanan put forward presidential bill on small-middle corporation (UKM) credit restructuring to President Megawati Soekarnoputri with a scheme of 50% haircut for cash payers and 40% for one-year-term payers. \par \par \uc2  In addition, for potential-to-develop UKM debtors but lacking capability to pay obligation in one year are proposed to be bestowed ten-year term with a 9% interest rate, while for un-prospective UKM debtors are recommended that their assets be auctioned off. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  expected to take effect late next month, said Alimarwan, encompasses UKM non-performing loans in IBRA, Directorate general of state accounts receivables and auction, government banks, as well as government-owned-majority stock banks. \par \par \uc2  Debt amount belonging to troubled debtors, according to State Minister for Cooperatives, stands at a total of Rp39.6 trillion distributed at IBRA (Rp4.8 trillion), Directorate general of State Electricity Company (Rp10.3 trillion), Bank Danamon and Bank Artha Graha (Rp4.8 trillion), and others Rp19.7 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "Materialization of UKM credit restructuring needs Presidential decree and approval from the departments concerned. President expected whatsoever step to be taken must be implemented in the end of March, consequently we are still having a review on it with \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Finance Minister," he said after meeting with the President at the Palace yesterday. \par \par \uc2  State Minister for Cooperatives also demanded that for UKM non-performing loans be granted one-year postponement of execution on UKM collateral assets in view that many complained of execution by creditors while new agreement has not been reached yet. \par \par \uc2  "Whereas in fact values of collaterals might double debt values. Thus, we are asking for a rescheduling that potential business can be developed," he elaborated. \par \par \uc2  Rp19 trillion in expenses \par \par \uc2  In the proposal to the President, State Minister for Cooperatives announced scheme of UKM non-performing loans encompassed a 50% haircut for cash payers and 40% for one-year term payers. \par \par \uc2  For UKM unable to pay in one year but with potential business, he called for some years of postponement in payment with a 9% interest rate. However, he agreed upon to auction off unpromising companies collateral assets. \par \par \uc2  "The proposition was delivered on the grounds that while huge debtors credit restructuring handled by FSPC need a crisis fund worth Rp400 trillion, crisis fund for UKM getting a 50% discount only reaches Rp19 trillion. It still has crisis cost, actually," he pointed out. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, State Minister of National Development Planning/chair of National Development Planning Board Kwik Kian Gie advised extension of shareholder obligation settlement should only take effect for one month after maturing time with half lower than BI Certificate interest rate. \par \par \uc2  "Though it is extended, I suggest facilities should be developed by the government could be extension of tenure for one month instead of ten years. Interest rate incentive is not a minimum of 9% but half lower than BI Certificate interest rate," he disclosed in work session with the House Commission IX discussing PKPS tenure extension at DPR/MPR compound. \par \par \uc2  As in work session one day earlier (Tuesday) with Finance Minister, State Minister of BUMN, and IBRA chairman, the House Commission IX only gave some notes of conclusion in the meeting lasted for four hours. Whether the House will accept or refuse, it will be deliberated in the intern commission meeting. \par \par \uc2  Some members of the House seemed to show respect to Kwik's argumentation regarding his stance to say no to PKPS tenure extension. Even some members of the House acknowledged that Kwik more critical than they are. \par \par \uc2  "I am become embarrassed myself, Pak Kwik appeared to know better and more critical toward government policies compared to us sitting here as \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  members," said member of the House Commission IX of Reform Fraction Hatta Taliwang. \par \par \uc2  In the 19-page paper delivered to the house, Kwik pointed out FSPC's decision on December 11, 2001 on PKPS tenure extension had drawn curiosities as well as created \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  instead of incentives. \par \par \uc2  According to him, the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by 'rubber conceptions' in the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that makes FSPC vulnerable to accusation that the latter deliberately made such elastic decision to enable it to be sold. Terms intended by Kwik among others are it is 'endeavored' that debtors pay 5% in 2002; regarding tenure with a term a maximum of ten years; and a minimum 9% of interest rate. \par \par \uc2  "It means the decision is vulnerable to accusation that FSPC gives room to IBRA so as to make its officials could decide a tenure of ten year should they are highly paid or nine year for slightly lower than that, eight years for small payment and so on," he remarked. \par \par \uc2  Kwik asserted PKPS tenure extension could not be taken, if the tycoons still do not want to pay, settlement must be through law enforcement. He alleged mean tycoons have bribed the government in order to extent shareholder obligation settlement. "It seems to be like that, they did not just come bringing argumentation but also some amount of money (that PKPS can be prolonged). (01/04/rah/esa). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis00200