\par\par \b \uc2  Floods push inflation higher, BPS reveals. \b0\par\par\uc2 493 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 March 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Inflation in February increased 1.5 percent from the previous month due to a combination of severe flood problems and the continuing effect of fuel price increases in January, the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) reported on Friday. \par \par \uc2  BPS said that, compared to the same month last year, inflation was 15.13 percent. \par \par \uc2  Analysts said that the high inflation level in February only strengthened their earlier conviction that the government's single digit inflation target of 9 percent for this year would not be attainable. \par \par \uc2  Many experts have said that inflation this year is likely to be between 11 percent and 13 percent. \par \par \uc2  Economist Ferry Hartoyo of Vickers Ballas Securities said that, with the high inflationary pressure, it would be difficult for \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to maintain its current \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of easing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Since the beginning of the year, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has tried to reduce its benchmark interest from near 18 percent late last year to around 16.88 percent now. \par \par \uc2  The interest rate reduction is crucial to help ease the government's burden in covering the interest of bonds issued to bail out banks. \par \par \uc2  The bureau said that the recent floods, which hit several parts of the country, including Jakarta, early last month had disrupted the supply of basic goods and consumer products, jacking up prices. \par \par \uc2  BPS said that food prices, which have the highest weighting in the Consumer Price Index basket, rose 3.11 percent month-on-month, while prices of processed food and beverages increased 0.8 percent. \par \par \uc2  Housing costs rose 1.67 percent, clothing 0.34 percent, health care 0.59 percent, education and recreation 0.40 percent, transportation and communications costs were up 1.16 percent. \par \par \uc2  BPS said that the increase in fuel prices by an average of 22 percent continued to push prices of goods and services higher in February. \par \par \uc2  Elsewhere, BPS said that exports in January grew slightly to US$4 billion from $3.99 billion in December, while imports fell to $1.89 billion from $2 billion. \par \par \uc2  Analysts said that, although the trade surplus in January was higher at $2.11 billion compared to $1.99 billion at the end of last year, the outlook for the overall trade picture remained grim amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly the U.S., one of Indonesia's main export destinations. \par \par \uc2  The government has said that this year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth target of 4 percent would continue to be driven by domestic consumption amid expected weak exports and low investment. \par \par \uc2  Some, however, are hopeful that the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will recover in the second half of this year, which will benefit Indonesia's exports. \par \par \uc2  The country's exports are mainly commodities and low-end manufacturing goods, which have been less affected by the current global downturn than exports from other countries in the region, which are dominated by high-tech goods. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020301dy3200060\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
