\par\par \b \uc2  IMF warns of new bank regulator. \b0\par\par\uc2 665 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 March 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Berni K. Moestafa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Creating a new financial regulator is by no means a simple task. And a new entity in the making shows the potential for dragging the banking sector through a detour in its road to recovery, according to one study by the International Monetary Fund (IMF). \par \par \uc2  The Financial Sector Supervisory Institution (FSSI), as it is called, will oversee the banking, securities, and insurance sectors under a role now held by various regulators. \par \par \uc2  The FSSI is expected to streamline \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the financial sector, with the government hoping to have it up and running by the end of this year. \par \par \uc2  But getting there would put banks through new risks that are part of the change process, according to the IMF. \par \par \uc2  "Any change process involves risks, and the greater the proposed structural change the greater the risk," the IMF said in a paper issued in 2000 that examined the pro and cons of unifying financial sector supervision. \par \par \uc2  For Indonesia, the transition period could plunge banks into new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a time many are still struggling to overcome the impact of the late '90s financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  "The change process may result in a serious reduction in existing regulatory capacity unless it is well-managed," the paper said. \par \par \uc2  "This is likely to be of particular concern in transitional or developing economies, where regulatory capacity may, in any case, already be relatively weak." \par \par \uc2  The paper said that in developing countries, where most financial sectors were centralized on banks, ample steps should be taken to assure banking supervision would not be compromised. \par \par \uc2  The local banking sector makes up about 80 percent of its financial sector, according to government estimates. \par \par \uc2  Any weakening in banking supervision would expose banks to added risk, as the threat of bank failure still remain high four years after the government bailed out the sector. \par \par \uc2  This has led \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to continue to retain 14 of the country's largest banks on its intensive-watch list, which normally is reserved for deeply troubled banks. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  supervises bank operations as part of maintaining financial stability, but will lose that authority once the FSSI takes charge. \par \par \uc2  Subsequently, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  was the first to air concern over the FSSI, which, due to its crucial role in the financial sector, \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials charged as too dubious. \par \par \uc2  They warned that a lack of coordination between the two bodies could slow the response time in the event another banking crisis loomed. \par \par \uc2  It is unclear how the FSSI will coordinate, within the financial sector, its role with that which \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  has on the monetary sector. Legislators have yet to produce an FSSI law. \par \par \uc2  "In any case, the benefits of change should be relatively clear and unambiguous before embarking on a proposed unification," the IMF's paper said. \par \par \uc2  The government said that one benefit of a unified supervision was to better control the operations of financial conglomerates. \par \par \uc2  Although many of the local ones have lost their ownership in banks as a result of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, many have maintained interests across a number of firms that are being supervised by different regulators. \par \par \uc2  "Experience has shown that, while these firms generally claim to have financial "fire walls" between their various operations, they often prove to be illusory when serious difficulties arise," the IMF's paper explained. \par \par \uc2  Another benefit, it said, was in developing rules that were more flexible than could be achieved with separate regulating agencies. \par \par \uc2  "Whereas the effectiveness of a system of separate agencies can be impeded by turf wars or a desire to pass the buck, these problems can be more easily limited and controlled in a unified regulatory organization," it said. \par \par \uc2  But it added that if the benefits of unification were not clear or the cost too high, more modest institutional changes might suffice. \par \par \uc2  These, it said, could range from the formation of a unified oversight board to shared facilities with the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020314dy3e0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
