now from their own experience lately, this is no easy task to accomplish. But President Megawati will certainly do India and the region a great service if she can somehow persuade the Indian leaders to calm sectarian sentiments. - The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2  SCENARIO OF THE U.S. TRAP \par \par \uc2  The United States' campaign, "War Against International Terrorism", seems to have claimed many victims both from among individual persons and organizations. These individuals and groups are easily caught under the suspicion of having connections to the Al Qaeda or other terrorist groups. Not only that, some Indonesian Moslems have been arrested in Singapore, Malaysia and the Philippines. However, both the US and the Indonesian apparatuses could not prove these people or groups' alleged connection to Al Qaeda, Osama bin Laden or other terrorist groups. The strange thing is that the Philippine apparatus seems to have known about the activities of the three Indonesians arrested there recently. Taking a close look at US efforts, it is actually not strange for the Philippines to know the activities of Linrung and his other two friends. An agreement between the US and the ASEAN in fighting terrorism, which includes information exchange, the recent visit of the US Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) director to the Asian region and a closed-door meeting with the Indonesian intelligence body, BIN, in Bali are believed to be the frame of the scenario. Thus, it is possible for Indonesia to have been trapped in the scenario. People or groups insisting on maintaining the Islamic law and are against the US attack on Afghanistan sooner or later would be easily branded as terrorists. - Republika \par \par \uc2  WHERE IS THE SUPPORT FOR SMEs? \par \par \uc2  It is ironic that small-and medium-scale enterprises and cooperatives have become "step children" in this country. When the crisis weakened our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , big companies collapsed but small and medium businesses showed their stamina in supporting the people's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . What has the government done to support them? Relatively nothing. The government's policies on small and medium enterprises did not assist them much. In short, the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for them until now continues to be insignificant. This is incompatible with the government's support for big companies. Conglomerate-owners always enjoy government facilities despite the fact that these came from the state's coffin. Small and medium enterprises indeed need government support, not only due to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reasons but also because of the demand of the US government through the International Monetary Fund (IMF), that Indonesia manage its small and medium enterprises, besides terrorism. The most important thing is the government's political will, whether it want to take side with the small-and medium-scale enterprises and cooperatives or not. - Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020020327dy3m0000m\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
