\par\par \b \uc2  Shunned by investors. \b0\par\par\uc2 776 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 March 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The negative assessment of the Indonesian business climate given by most of the Japanese investors surveyed by the Japan Bank for International Cooperation (JBIC) last year is yet another sign that the country is still shunned by most foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  But the survey's findings - that Japanese small and medium-sized companies had begun relocating their operations from Indonesia to other countries in Asia - are nonetheless greatly worrisome, as Japanese investors are usually more flexible in adapting to Indonesian conditions than American or European business investors. \par \par \uc2  The World Investment Report 2001, published by the Geneva-based United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) in September, also found that an increasing number of Japanese investors in ASEAN countries had relocated their plants to China, and that direct foreign investment flows to Indonesia remained negative - a signal that the wave of capital flight that started in late 1997 had not stopped. \par \par \uc2  Yet more perturbing among the JBIC survey findings was the fact that the Indonesian government seemed scarcely concerned about the disturbing trend, doing virtually nothing to address grievances of foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  This is alarming indeed. Without fresh foreign capital, experts said, the country will never regain the sustainable, robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of at least 7 percent a year needed to absorb the new entrants to the labor market. \par \par \uc2  The 3.3 percent growth last year, down from 4.8 percent in 2000, was fueled mainly by domestic consumer demand and exports. \par \par \uc2  But even these two locomotives will eventually run out of steam without new investment. \par \par \uc2  If domestic consumers continue \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , savings will drop steadily, and they will eventually run out of money. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian export competitiveness will also decline if existing foreign investors remain discouraged from making additional investments to retool and modernize plant equipment to improve efficiency and product quality so as to diversify product lines. \par \par \uc2  Since most big business groups are still crippled by mountains of bad debt, and the banking industry may take another three to five years to resume full functions to pump liquidity to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  foreign investment is, in the short term at least, most likely the main source of fresh capital. \par \par \uc2  The country's main attractions to foreign investors are its rich natural resources, potentially large market and highly competitive labor wage structure. \par \par \uc2  But a host of new and old problems have made these attractions less meaningful for investment. \par \par \uc2  Legal and regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is now looming over new investment in natural resources that are located mostly outside Java, especially after the launching of regional autonomy in January 2001. \par \par \uc2  The central government has given local administrations full authority to license investment in such areas as mining (outside oil and gas), fishing and forestry. \par \par \uc2  But foreign investors do not feel comfortable with making deals only with local administrations since the international community, notably suppliers and creditors, do not recognize contracts that are not ratified by the central government in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, basic infrastructure has begun to crumble in many provinces due to an acute lack of maintenance \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the past four years. \par \par \uc2  Poor infrastructure increases the cost of doing business, making the capital costs of investment projects abnormally high. \par \par \uc2  The domestic market is no longer a great advantage now because of the depressed \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition. In fact, the manufacturing industry is now suffering from a big excess capacity. \par \par \uc2  Even low-cost labor, which lured thousands of small and medium-size investors from South Korea and Taiwan in 1970 to 1995, is no longer a big positive factor either. \par \par \uc2  The increasing militancy and antiforeign investment sentiment among trade unions is scaring off investors. \par \par \uc2  It goes without saying that these problems need to be addressed immediately - but with a properly selected priority scale. Certainly, the general business climate should be improved steadily to encourage existing investors to expand their capacities, or modernize their plants. \par \par \uc2  But this is an ongoing, gradual process. \par \par \uc2  Given the desperate need for foreign investment, contingency programs are required. \par \par \uc2  Since investment in green-field projects seems now feasible only in resource-based ventures given the excess capacity in the manufacturing industry, the government should act immediately to remove the legal and regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in mining, fisheries and such infrastructure as power generation and road and port development, especially because investment in these areas has a long gestation period. \par \par \uc2  Next on the priority list is expediting the disposal of the thousands of distressed assets currently under the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency and privatization of state companies. \par \par \uc2  It is therefore futile for the government to expect new investment in Indonesia's manufacturing industry if these distressed assets do not get new, credible investors. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020