\par\par \b \uc2  Legislators still insist on having a say in privatization plan. \b0\par\par\uc2 593 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 April 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Legislators are still insisting on having a say in the government's 2002 privatization program, despite last week's approval by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , signaling fragile support for the vital yet troubled program. \par \par \uc2  Last week the government said it would launch the sale of 25 state companies after securing approval from the House's Commission IX, which oversees financial affairs. \par \par \uc2  Commission vice chairman Faisal Baasir, however, said the deal did not rule out further debate on the planned sales. \par \par \uc2  "What we approved was only in general terms, further discussion will still be needed for more in-depth examination," Faisal told The Jakarta Post over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  More discussions could add to \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the privatization program bogged down by resistance from workers and politicians riding on national sentiments. \par \par \uc2  At stake is Rp 6.5 trillion (US$679 million) to help plug the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of around Rp 42 trillion this year. \par \par \uc2  Also crucial are efforts to woo back foreign investment that would lend the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  a boost, which the tight state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  is unable to. \par \par \uc2  Commission IX's approval followed a series of closed-door meetings, and was preceded by hearings with Commission V, which oversees state enterprises. \par \par \uc2  But that might not be enough, Faisal said. \par \par \uc2  The government might not only have to return to Commission IX for more talks, but could also be called in by other commissions should a problem in one state company arise, he explained. \par \par \uc2  Problems loom. Workers at state companies have added to the pressure against planned sales to foreign investors, calling them a sting to national pride. \par \par \uc2  Last week, a group of 50 people claiming to represent all labor unions at state-owned enterprises urged the government to cancel its privatization program. \par \par \uc2  They demanded a privatization law be set up first, and the involvement of workers during privatization talks. A law on that is being drafted by the government. \par \par \uc2  Commission V chairman Suryadharma Ali added that the government also needed the consent of commissions that were in charge of industries under which the state companies were operating. \par \par \uc2  "... because if it (the approval) is not comprehensive and not integrated, it will cause problems in the future," he said. \par \par \uc2  By law, the government is not obliged to seek the House's approval for its privatization program. \par \par \uc2  Experts have long urged the government to come to an agreement with legislators on privatization guidelines to avoid excessive interference by legislators. \par \par \uc2  Legislators last year nearly canceled the sale of state-owned palm oil plantations to a Malaysian company, asserting that assets like these should remain under Indonesian control. \par \par \uc2  A planned sale that may rip open old conflicts, is that of cement maker PT Semen Gresik to Cemex SA de CV of Mexico. \par \par \uc2  Backed by local politicians, fierce protests by Semen Gresik's workers killed off three years of efforts to sell the company to Cemex in a deal worth around $520 million. \par \par \uc2  Now employees from Bank Central Asia (BCA), state-owned telecommunication firms PT Telkom and PT Indosat have taken to the streets in protest of their privatization plans. \par \par \uc2  Former manpower minister and labor activist, Bomer Pasaribu said earlier the government had to do more to involve workers in its privatization program. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Indonesian Prosperity Trade Union (SBSI) Muchtar Pakpahan concurred, saying: "The government had to change the old way of making privatization \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by also listening to the aspirations of the workers to gain support for the program". \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020408dy480000i\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Japan fully supports RI at Paris Club III. \b0\par\par\uc2 580 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 April 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Tokyo fully supports Jakarta efforts to ask for debt rescheduling payments in Paris Club III talks starting today, a Keidanren executive says. \par \par \uc2  Deputy chairman of Keidanren - grouping Japan biggest companies managing high-scale investments in Southeast Asia - Shigeji Ueshima asserts efforts toward Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery are on the right track. \par \par \uc2  So, he continues, Japan throws its full support on Indonesia to get debts rescheduling, even though it is the Indonesian government's responsibility. \par \par \uc2  "We believe Paris Club talks will go on successfully. But all these depend on other creditor countries," he said in Jakarta over the weekend. \par \par \uc2  According to the economist at CSIS Pande Radja Silalahi, Japan's support will beget positive impacts because the country is Indonesian greatest creditor. We welcome the support, he continues, as Jepan has indicated to cut its aids to other countries. \par \par \uc2  Frans Seda, president's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultant, asserts Japan has its own way to help Indonesia. "It never makes rescheduling, but (in reality) it is okay, how much you want to pay. It eventually gives more (debts)." \par \par \uc2  In this way, he continues, Japan differs with other creditors. "However this way will perhaps change, too," he says answering the question of the possibility for Japan to impose haircut. \par \par \uc2  But he declines to give a lot of comments, because "There have been assertion from donor countries that Indonesian officials talk too much." \par \par \uc2  Japan constitutes the biggest creditor for Indonesia in the Paris Club as the country had provided US$2.4 billion (from the total US$4.2 billion) and US$2.7 billion (from the total US$5.8 billion) respectively in Paris Club I and II. Paris Club are scheduled to held meeting in Paris today through April 12 to discuss the debt restructuring of Indonesia, Argentina, Ecuador, Ivory Coast, and Nigeria. \par \par \uc2  Optimistic \par \par \uc2  Earlier expert staff of minister of finance, Anggito Abimanyu, admitted that Indonesia had submitted a rescheduling proposal for over 20 years for debts worth of US$5.5 billion which will mature between April 1, 2002 and December 31, 2003. Minister of finance Boediono is optimistic over the support from Paris Club creditors, after launching a road show last month. \par \par \uc2  Silalahi adds chance for Indonesia to secure debt rescheduling worth of US$5.5 billion is widely open. The problem is, he continues, the periods of rescheduling. \par \par \uc2  Creditors will ask what is the basis for asking rescheduling over 20 years. The Paris Club members thus require the clarity of Indonesia's commitment, for example on worries about the tendency of erratic government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, Silalahi says creditors confidence could be the barometer indicating whether Indonesia is still attractive for investors. The problems is that the longer the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  remain the more investors are getting bored and eventually woul