\par\par \b \uc2  INDON  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2  TO GROW 3 PCT IN 2002, ADB SAYS. \b0\par\par\uc2 402 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 April 2002\par \uc2 ANTARA - The Indonesian National News Agency\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Asia Pulse Pte Limited. Asia Pulse gives no warranty or guarantee as to the accuracy of the information, Asia Pulse shall not be liable for errors or omissions in, or delays or interruptions to or cessation of delivery of, the data through its negligence or otherwise.\par \par \uc2  Jakarta, April 9 (ANTARA) - The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has predicted that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow 3 percent this year against 3.3 percent last year. The decline in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will be the result of the sluggish demand in the consumption sector early this year, although it will pick up again middle of the year, deputy director of the ADB's representative for Indonesia, David Jay Green, said when presenting the Asian Development Outlook 2002 on Tuesday. The Manila-based bank predicted that the prospects of the global market in 2002 and 2003 will be better than those of last year in line with progress achieved in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms. "The prudential monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies will boost a 3.6 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2003. However, it is very difficult to achieve a pre-crisis \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 7 percent to 10 percent," he said. He said last year's 3.3 percent growth was also weak compared to 4.8 percent the year before. \par \par \uc2  Actually, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  began to recover from the crisis in 2000 but the condition was not maintained, particularly because of investment \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and a slowdown in the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he pointed out. While private spendings grew 6 percent, exports and imports last year dropped 26 percent from the year before, he said. The bank noted that the manufacturing sector posted a 4.3 percent growth last year. While the service sector posted a robust growth last year, the agricultural sector grew only less than 1 percent due to a myriad problems in rural areas, he said. He said this year's state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will face a serious problem, particularly in the management of domestic and foreign debts. To overcome the problem, the government must try to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts, increase exports, create political stability, and attract new investments, he said. The bank underscored the need for the government to improve immediately its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and state bureaucracy, and enhance political certainty and security. Meanwhile, senior ADB official, Shiladityha Chatterjee, said the bank has pledged loans worth US$ 855 million and technical grants worth US$ 18.3 million to Indonesia. The loans will be used among others to rehabilitate coral reefs, increase poor farmers' income, improve the management of non-bank financial institutions, develop export-oriented small and medium enterprises, build power plants, and eradicate poverty. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020020411dy49000h6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
