\par\par \b \uc2  JETRO asks RI to introduce  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\uc2  incentives for investment. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Adianto P. Simamora, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 472 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 April 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  President of Japan External Trade Organization (JETRO) Hiroyuki Kato said Indonesia must follow the steps of its peers in the region by providing \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives to woo more investments from Japan. \par \par \uc2  "The government needs to quickly provide \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives to attract foreign investors, particularly the Japanese, as other ASEAN countries and China have offered such incentives," he told The Jakarta Post on Tuesday on the sidelines of a seminar. \par \par \uc2  ASEAN is the Association of South East Asian Nations. \par \par \uc2  Hiroyuki also said that the government had to work harder to improve the investment climate here. \par \par \uc2  "Japanese investors see the investment climate in Indonesia is not so good," he said, pointing to legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the lack of supporting industries. \par \par \uc2  Last week, a visiting delegation of Japan's Federation of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Corporations (Keidanren) led by its chairman Takashi Imai also urged the government to do more to improve the investment climate here. \par \par \uc2  According to a recent survey by the Japan Bank of International Cooperation (JBIC), Indonesia has continued to fall further behind China and Thailand in the competition for Japanese investment, and it could be overtaken by Vietnam and India if it does not take immediate steps to improve its investment climate. \par \par \uc2  Japan has been Indonesia's largest investor and creditor. The government is scheduled to meet with official creditor nations grouped in the Paris Club on Thursday to seek a rescheduling facility of around US$5.5 billion in official debt maturing this year and next. Minister of Finance Boediono, who visited Japan last week, said that the Japanese government was committed to supporting Indonesia's bid for a rescheduling facility. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors have largely shunned Indonesia after the country plunged into an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crisis in 1998. \par \par \uc2  The regaining of foreign investments is important for the recovery of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  There has been word that the country's new investment law, currently being drafted by the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM), would include \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  The new bill was supposed to have been submitted to the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  last week. BKPM officials said that the bill would be completed soon and be submitted to the House for approval within the next two months. \par \par \uc2  Hiroyuki said that Japanese investors would welcome such a move. \par \par \uc2  He said that Indonesia could adopt the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentive facility introduced by the Chinese government, under which foreign investors were exempted from corporate \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the first two years in operation, and were only obliged to pay half of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  from year three through year five. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have said that while competition among Asian countries for Japanese investment has been tight, Indonesia has done very little to attract the yen. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020410dy4a0006h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich3