\par\par \b \uc2  RI's  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  growth to lag behind neighbors'. \b0\par\par\uc2 542 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 April 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year will lag behind that of other Asian developing countries, the United Nations said on Friday, citing massive debts cripple the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 's ability to stimulate growth. \par \par \uc2  The United Nations \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) found that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospect in the medium term remained bleak. \par \par \uc2  "We have to admit that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will not be encouraging until 2004. That will hamper efforts to create jobs for new labor force," former ESCAP economist Prabowo said during the presentation of the commission's 2002 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social survey of Asia and the Pacific. \par \par \uc2  He said that while other economies in Southeast Asia would rebound sharply in 2003 and 2004, Indonesia's growth would likely stay at around 4 to 5 percent. \par \par \uc2  ESCAP said an upturn in global demand led by a rebounding U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will drive the region's growth. \par \par \uc2  "This year, the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to grow by 3.8 percent. While the growth figures for the next two years stand at 4.9 percent and 4.6 percent, respectively," Prabowo said. \par \par \uc2  By contrast, Malaysia and Singapore's economies might grow by 5.1 and 5.8 percent respectively in 2003. While in 2004, he said, their economies could grow by another 6.1 and 5.7 percent. \par \par \uc2  Laying the blame on massive \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debts, Prabowo said Indonesia's state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  could not generate enough steam to drive the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  This year about 40 percent of government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been allotted to serve foreign and domestic debt payments. \par \par \uc2  The government spends less on development than it does on domestic debt payments, which amounts to around Rp 59 trillion (about $63 billion). \par \par \uc2  Almost all of this debt, will go into banks with government bonds which they took when the government bailed them out from the late 90s financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  A \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  official has said that almost 45 percent of banks' revenue last year was still paid by taxpayers' money. \par \par \uc2  Official data show the country owes some $130 billion, which accounts for more than 80 percent of this year's estimated gross domestic product (GDP) of $160 billion. \par \par \uc2  That leaves the government with limited options to invest in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , meaning growth rests more with how much the private sector can spare. \par \par \uc2  But with an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  investment climate, a banking sector in the doldrums, and companies still undergoing debt restructuring talks, economists warned against expecting much from private investors. \par \par \uc2  At the receiving end of this situation are the poor, Prabowo said. \par \par \uc2  Not only will a cut in development \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  mean less money for social welfare programs, but the subsequent slower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth means that not enough jobs are created to absorb the millions of new entrance in the job market. \par \par \uc2  ESCAP urged Indonesia secure policies that enhance \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth where the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  cannot. \par \par \uc2  This translates into pushing ahead with the government's structural reforms program. \par \par \uc2  They include the restructuring of the banking and the private sectors, the privatization of state enterprises, upholding the supremacy of the law, and strengthening institutions and governance to support positive business and investment climate. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020429dy4r0005n\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI still unable to change the yield curve. \b0\par\par\uc2 381 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 April 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  BI official revealed there are three factors taken into consideration for banks in investing their money, while the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  still cannot change the yield curve, not until the T-Bill is issued. \par \par \uc2  BI Head of Law Bureau Halim Alamsyah said it won't be easy to change the banks deposits from the short term interest into the long term one. Thus far, there are three factors considered to decide in which term they will invest. \par \par \uc2  The first is the banks confidence upon the current macro condition and situation. If things are getting better, they will opt to save in the long-term deposits. \par \par \uc2  Second is the banks' expectation on interest rate. If they predict it will fall, then they will tend to lock up to the long term BI certificate (SBI). \par \par \uc2  And the last one is their consideration on the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and politic situation in the country. If the situation is getting worse, they will prefer to save in long-term deposits. \par \par \uc2  A banking analyst Budi Hikmat said earlier BI should keep 