\par\par \b \uc2  Bali Commitment in limbo as talks near end. \b0\par\par\uc2 758 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 June 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Nusa Dua, Bali \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  continued to cloud the fate of the Bali Commitment in the final hours of negotiation, as its draft plan on sustainable development remained clogged with unresolved issues, leading to either weaker commitments, or more negotiation in Johannesburg, South Africa. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian delegation reiterated on Thursday that the talks would end in Bali despite statements by senior UN officials indicating otherwise. Several non-governmental organizations urged delegates not to compromise in Bali for a weaker document. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian delegate Makarim Wibisono said that as long as talks were still going on, there should not be fear of a weak Bali Commitment. \par \par \uc2  "There haven't been any discussions at all to extend the negotiation (to Johannesburg)," Makarim said. "The mood here is that everyone wants to finalize it." \par \par \uc2  Delegates have been in Bali since May 27 for the drafting of the Bali Commitment - an action plan that will set the tone for the global development over the next 10 years by balancing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development with social and environmental interests. \par \par \uc2  The upcoming world summit on sustainable development in Johannesburg in August is expected to attract over one hundred heads of state who will endorse the Bali Commitment with a political declaration. \par \par \uc2  Yet the long-standing North-South division in the world reared its ugly head in Bali. Developed and developing countries disagree on whether or not the Bali Commitment should get the backing of new financial resources. \par \par \uc2  Debates on the financial commitments remained tough, said Lowell Flanders a senior United Nations official tracking progress on the negotiation. \par \par \uc2  He said talks centered on demands to link developed countries' aid commitments during the conference on financing development at Monterrey, Mexico, with programs under the Bali Commitment. \par \par \uc2  Earlier this year, developed countries pledged to set aside US$30 billion in aid by the year 2006 to help combat poverty. \par \par \uc2  But Monterrey left open the question of how and where developed countries would distribute the aid. \par \par \uc2  A number of activists raised concerns that some of the money would come in the form of foreign investments and trade incentives rather than pure grants. \par \par \uc2  They also pointed out that agricultural \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  were six times the amount of the Monterrey aid, and was harming developing countries, yet developed countries refused to cut back the \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The Group 77 plus China, which is the developing countries' negotiation block, demanded that developed countries raise their aid levels. \par \par \uc2  They also want the funds pledged at Monterrey to help finance sustainable development programs under the Bali Commitment. \par \par \uc2  Debates now focus on whether developed countries should go beyond Monterrey or whether the Bali Commitment should merely endorse the Monterrey pledge. \par \par \uc2  An Indonesian delegate, who refused to be named, said that the country would not settle for anything less than "beyond Monterrey." \par \par \uc2  According to Flanders, as of Thursday neither side showed signs of backing down from their positions, while in other contentious issues, compromises were being made. \par \par \uc2  Among them is the debate on ocean affairs, where delegates agreed to emphasize the exploitation of marine life on conservation instead of sustainable use. \par \par \uc2  But other outstanding issues, marked by bracketed and bold paragraphs in the negotiated draft plan, continue to dominate the draft plan. \par \par \uc2  "At the rate that we are proceeding at this stage, we may not have a lot to include," Flanders said. \par \par \uc2  Given the slow progress, he said, delegates might decide to continue negotiations in Johannesburg, possibly discussing finance and trade. \par \par \uc2  "It's very possible that countries would like to keep things open until Johannesburg," he said. \par \par \uc2  United Nations Development Program (UNDP) administrator Malloch Brown echoed the NGO's calls not to be afraid to "take the brackets to Johannesburg." \par \par \uc2  NGO member Antonie Hill of Oxfam International urged delegates to resume talks in Johannesburg, saying talks on finance and trade were going nowhere. \par \par \uc2  "Everybody is waiting for the finance and trade thing, until that is resolved or unless some movements happen there, the other step is meaningless. It's not real commitment, it's not something that's implementable," he said. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian People's Forum of local NGOs and groups representing among others women, youth and indigenous people took a harder stance, rejecting the Bali Commitment and boycotting the Johannesburg summit altogether. \par \par \uc2  They charged governments with excluding their interests in the draft plan in favor of business interests. \par \par \uc2  He said outstanding issues in the draft plan of implementation for the Bali Commitment, had gone nowhere, and were overwhelming given the tight deadline on Friday. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020607dy670000p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
