\par\par \b \uc2  Cancellation of Niaga sale. \b0\par\par\uc2 769 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 June 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  What a shame! A three-month sale process, claimed to have been carried out through the cleanest and most transparent of competitive bids, ended in a shambles. \par \par \uc2  The government's decision to cancel Bank Niaga's strategic sale will certainly dampen investor interest in future divestment programs and slow down the process of rebuilding market confidence in the fragile banking industry. \par \par \uc2  Annulling a transaction because of what the government considered unacceptably low prices, which were, after all, made through one of the cleanest and most transparent bidding processes ever carried out by the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency, will cause \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in future bank sales. \par \par \uc2  The government seems stubbornly unaware that it already owns or controls all the largest banks in the country, and unless most of these are made available to private investors the banking industry will remain fragile, held afloat mainly by the government's blanket guarantee on deposits. \par \par \uc2  Was it really that the Rp 20 to Rp 30 per share?? offered by the two final bidders, Australia's ANZ Banking Group and Malaysian Commerce Asset Holding - for 51 percent of Bank Niaga - was unacceptably low? Certainly so, as that is way below Rp 70, the current price of Bank Niaga shares on the Jakarta stock exchange, and the Rp 100 average share price over the past three months. \par \par \uc2  The government and several independent analysts argue that accepting such dreadfully low prices would have caused too great a loss to taxpayers, who had already injected Rp 9 trillion to recapitalize the medium-sized bank. \par \par \uc2  However, many other analysts argue that comparing the final bid prices with the Bank Niaga market quotation is not relevant because less than 3 percent of its 78.2 billion issued shares are traded on the stock exchange. The price formed on the exchange does not truly reflect market sentiment regarding the bank's prospects. Moreover, the Rp 20 to Rp 30 price range is already greater than the Rp 15 per share that is now the book value of Bank Niaga. \par \par \uc2  In assessing the bid prices, one should also consider that Indonesia's macroeconomic fundamentals are not yet sufficiently encouraging for banks to grow soundly and strongly. Investing in a bank under such critical \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions is highly risky. \par \par \uc2  It is worth recalling that almost all of Bank Niaga's capital consists of illiquid government bonds. Yet more disadvantageous is that most of these bonds carry a fixed coupon rate of 12.5 percent, much lower than the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's benchmark interest rate, now about 15.5 percent. \par \par \uc2  Neither does Bank Niaga possess a strong franchise in a particular market niche. Its bad loans of Rp 645 billion are only about 8 percent of total lending, or lower than the average in the industry. But it also carries Rp 2.8 trillion in its credit portfolio, which is on the verge of falling into the category of problem loans. The slightest deterioration in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  could transform these loans into liabilities. \par \par \uc2  Given this fragile state of affairs and the fierce competition within the industry (as almost all domestic and foreign banks now compete in the retail market), Bank Niaga desperately needs a new controlling owner, a strategic investor with a good track record in bank management and sizable financial resources to strengthen market confidence in the bank. \par \par \uc2  Strategic sales are surely the best method for reinvigorating banks, not only because they are the best way of attracting long-term investors who can bring in synergy. The weak Jakarta stock exchange simply cannot absorb large-scale equity issues right now and the investing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  is unlikely to be interested in buying bank shares until the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  regains a sustainable, robust growth. \par \par \uc2  Cancellation of the Bank Niaga strategic sale on highly subjective and debatable grounds will certainly affect the sales of Bank Danamon, Bank Lippo, Bank Mandiri and Bank International Indonesia (BII), which are scheduled for the second half of this year. \par \par \uc2  This is quite worrying indeed, because the longer the banks remain under state control or ownership the greater will be the contingent liabilities for the government under the blanket guarantee program, and the more hazardous will be the risk. \par \par \uc2  The government is well advised to realize that only strategic investors will be able to accelerate the restructuring of the fragile banking industry. The government simply does not have the technical competence, financial resources and, most importantly, credibility, to raise the banks onto a stronger footing. And without sound and strong banks the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be able to return to sustainable, high growth. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020612dy6c00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
