\par\par \b \uc2  'Cabinet cracks the last thing business community needs'. \b0\par\par\uc2 667 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 June 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Dadan Wijaksana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Apparent cracks between \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers over whether Indonesia should maintain policies sponsored by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) could prove costly to efforts to speed up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, an economist said. \par \par \uc2  "It impacts the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a negative way. When a government official publicly criticizes a government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , that will eventually create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is bad for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) economist Pande told The Jakarta Post on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  Pande was commenting on signs that the Cabinet, particularly \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers, is becoming increasingly divided over the role of the IMF and its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prescriptions. \par \par \uc2  On one side is Coordinating Minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Tjakti, who insists that the country still needs the IMF until the end of next year. On the other side is State Minister of National Development Planning Kwik Kian Gie, who has launched a campaign to persuade the government to discontinue the IMF-sponsored \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  program after it ends in November 2002. \par \par \uc2  The two sides have been trading barbs in the newspapers. Appeals by President Megawati Soekarnoputri for her ministers not to go \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  with their differences seem to have gone unheeded. \par \par \uc2  Pande said it was important for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers to cooperate in designing and implementing policies to help the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recover quickly. \par \par \uc2  Despite growing opposition to the IMF, Dorodjatun, Minister of Finance Boediono and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Sjahril Sabirin signed late on Tuesday a new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform plan with the IMF, in exchange for the disbursement of the fund's next US$340 million loan tranche. The IMF is arranging a three-year $5 billion loan package for the country. \par \par \uc2  Kwik, a former chief \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister in the administration of Abdurrahman Wahid, has repeatedly and openly attacked some of the key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies agreed to by the government and the IMF, saying they will only push the country deeper into crisis. \par \par \uc2  Among other things, Kwik has criticized the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of selling local banks before replacing the recapitalization bonds held by them. He says the proceeds the government stands to receive from the sale of the banks is much less than the amount it will have to allocate for the bonds' interest payments. \par \par \uc2  Kwik points to the sale of BCA as an example. He says that because the bank holds close to Rp 60 trillion worth of recap bonds, the government has to pay the bank more than Rp 5 trillion each year in interest payments, almost the same amount it received from the sale of the bank. \par \par \uc2  Kwik has questioned the need for the country's continued dependence on the fund, saying Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be growing even without the IMF. \par \par \uc2  Standing firmly on the other side of the argument are the remaining \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministers, led by Dorodjatun. They insist that Indonesia continues to require the assistance of the IMF in guiding the country out of the prolonged crisis. \par \par \uc2  As arguments among the country's top \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  officials intensify, there is concern that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will suffer. \par \par \uc2  Pande is of this opinion, saying that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the last thing the business community needs. \par \par \uc2  "The business community will feel this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a threat to their businesses. This will affect our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , this is dangerous," Pande said. \par \par \uc2  Umar Juoro, an economist at the Center for Information and Development Studies (CIDES), also noted that differences between the two sides were wide enough to create problems in the future. \par \par \uc2  He suggested the President Megawati Soekarnoputri address the situation to avoid any more confusion. \par \par \uc2  "The President should come forward and bravely say what the country should do about the IMF. I think this would cool the tension a bit," Umar told the Post. \par \par \uc2  However, when asked whether it was necessary for the President to dismiss Kwik from the Cabinet, Pande and Umar were quick to say that this would be way out of proportion and would create new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020614dy6e0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
