\par\par \b \uc2  'Govt must quickly resolve Manulife fiasco'. \b0\par\par\uc2 777 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 June 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  3 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Rendi A. Witular and A'an Suryana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Experts warned the government not to ignore nor underestimate the effect the Manulife fiasco would have on legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country, and predicted that the impact on the ailing \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be severe. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Committee (KPEN) Sofyan Wanandi said on Tuesday that if the government did not immediately take action to resolve the problem, badly needed foreign investment, crucial to helping push \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, would not materialize. \par \par \uc2  He added that the Manulife case was not the first as investors had often complained about the country's weak legal system and raised doubts about the security of foreign investments here. \par \par \uc2  "Such cases have often occurred in the country and the government is frequently late in handling the fallout. If cases like this continue to occur, no foreign investor will invest his money in this country" Sofyan told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  The Commercial Court on June 13 ruled PT Asuransi Jiwa Manulife Indonesia (AJMI) bankrupt in a controversial ruling that has strained relations between the Indonesian and Canadian governments. AJMI is the local unit of giant Canadian insurer Manulife Financial Corp. \par \par \uc2  The Manulife bankruptcy ruling has added to the list of foreign investors badly burnt by the lack of legal certainty in this country. \par \par \uc2  One prominent example is the situation facing East Kalimantan coal mining giant PT Kaltim Prima Coal (KPC), which is equally owned by Anglo-Australian mining company Rio Tinto and British-American oil and gas company BP. \par \par \uc2  The South Jakarta District Court in March issued a ruling sequestering the assets of KPC following a US$776 million lawsuit filed by the East Kalimantan provincial administration. Through the lawsuit, the provincial administration sought to pressure KPC to sell 51 percent of its shares to the province. \par \par \uc2  Under its contract of work, KPC is obliged to sell a 51 percent stake to either the Indonesian government, state-owned companies or Indonesian-controlled private firms this year. There is no clause in the contract stipulating that the stake must be sold to the province. \par \par \uc2  International lenders like the World Bank, International Monetary Fund, Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI), and even the Paris Club of creditor nations have long asked the government to heed the complaints of investors in the country, particularly with regard to the lack of legal certainty and security concerns. \par \par \uc2  But Sofyan said the government seemed to have learned nothing from past experience. \par \par \uc2  "The government is not doing its homework. This is a sign that the government is underestimating these cases," said Sofyan heatedly. \par \par \uc2  Sofyan also criticized senior government officials who showed no concern for the investment climate by making counterproductive comments over the Manulife case. \par \par \uc2  Economist Pande Radja Silalahi of the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) shared Sofyan's views, saying that the Manulife case was yet another \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations disaster for the country, which had been struggling to attract foreign investors since the 1997 financial crisis. \par \par \uc2  "There's always a risk involved in investment. But as long as the risks can be predicted, this will not pose a problem for foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  But, the lack of legal certainty is a different case as it is unpredictable," he said, adding that investors highly prized legal certainty. \par \par \uc2  Amitava Banerjee from the International Finance Corporation concurred, saying that continuing capital flight and the drop in private investment here reflected the lack of confidence in the country's business environment. \par \par \uc2  From an inflow of US$11.5 billion in 1996, private capital has been flowing out of Indonesia at about US$10 billion a year over the last four years, Banerjee said. \par \par \uc2  "An important element in a market friendly environment is a court system that can protect property rights and enforce contracts," he said. \par \par \uc2  Learning from the facts, it was a high time for the parties concerned in Indonesia to restore the confidence of foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  The bankruptcy ruling against AJMI was made after the receiver of the now defunct PT Dharmala Sakti Sejahtera (DSS), the one-time partner of Manulife in AJMI, filed a lawsuit over a 1999 unpaid dividend. Manulife, which has filed an appeal with the Supreme Court, said that the shareholders did not authorize the payment of a dividend for the period in question. \par \par \uc2  According to the finance ministry, AJMI is actually a healthy and solvent company. \par \par \uc2  The verdict has prompted concern among legal observers, who say that it is perverse and unjustifiable. \par \par \uc2  "This is the most absurd decision that I've ever heard of from the Commercial Court," noted lawyer Amir Syamsuddin has said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020626dy6q00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
