\par\par \b \uc2  Legal  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty \highlight\uc2  plays part in FDI decline - Theo. \b0\par\par\uc2 589 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 June 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Dadan Wijaksana, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Foreign direct investment (FDI) approvals for the first five months of the year has fallen by almost 60 percent over the same period recorded in 2001, failing to keep up with the recent steady signs of rising investor confidence. \par \par \uc2  Data from the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) showed that as of May 30, FDI approvals reached US$1.67 billion spread over 402 projects, a far cry compared to the $3.98 billion posted during the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  Although BKPM Chairman Theo F. Toemion attributed the sharp decline to accumulated problems lingering in the country, he also admitted that legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  had played a significant part in diminishing foreign investor confidence. \par \par \uc2  "Even before the Manulife case erupted, the international community very interested to see how Indonesia honored legitimate contracts and how the law was being upheld. \par \par \uc2  "... So, the efforts to lure FDI will always be hampered if we're not serious about legal matters," Theo told reporters on Thursday on the sidelines of a hearing with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ' Commission V on trade and industry. \par \par \uc2  Theo was referring to the much-debated verdict by the Commercial Court declaring bankrupt the local unit of Canada's Manulife Financial Corp., PT Asuransi Jiwa Manulife Indonesia (AJMI). \par \par \uc2  Despite the fact that the legal process is still following the company's appeal to the Supreme Court, the controversial ruling has aroused controversy, and even suggestions of wholesale reform in the country's legal system to provide protection to foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Theo deplored the fact that such an incident could occur just as the country was starting to see signs of improving confidence, as evident in the significant rise in the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, and in the capital market. \par \par \uc2  "... it was hoped that the recent strengthening of the rupiah and a bullish (stock market) index would generate higher capital inflows. Now, they're going to wait for positive signals on how we handle these causes celebres, like Manulife, for example," Theo added. \par \par \uc2  The country's capital and financial markets have been on the rise since the start of the year, mostly due to the government's commitment to its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform programs, which were believed to be beginning to entice capital inflows back into the domestic market. \par \par \uc2  However, unlike such short-term investments, direct investment is seen as having a bigger impact on stimulating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  So far, the attempts to stimulate direct investments, both domestic and foreign, have been relatively fruitless. \par \par \uc2  FDI approvals have been declining ever since the country lurched into the 1997-1998 crisis, in accordance with a loss of the appetite for investment on the part of foreigners due to various problems, notably security disturbances, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political instability, and legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Last year, FDI approvals dropped by 41.5 percent to $9.02 billion compared to the previous year. \par \par \uc2  As for domestic investment, the data also showed a drop in approvals during the January to May period from Rp 12.7 trillion in 2001 to Rp 9.4 trillion this year. \par \par \uc2  For 2001, domestic investment amounted to Rp 58 trillion while foreign investment reached $9 billion. \par \par \uc2  The BKPM data also revealed that the most popular sectors among foreign investors during the period were trading, with 171 projects, services, with 53 projects, the machine, basic metal industries and electronics sector with 28 projects, transportation and telecommunications with 23 projects and the textile sector with 16 projects. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020628dy6s0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
