orking Committee are embroiled in a debate on the second-round vote in direct presidential elections, whether it should be done by the people or by the assembly. Outside the assembly, a number of experts have offered different thoughts. Some have come up with the idea of a one-round presidential election, while others have suggested that the next president be elected after members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) and local \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  assemblies (DPRD) are appointed. The essence of the thoughts is clear - that it is the people and not the MPR who are entitled to elect the president and vice president. Experience has thought us that the assembly's choice is not always the people's choice. The assembly can abuse the people's sovereignty. It can act as a "horse-trading" institute to serve the interests of those in the elite. Thus, the second-round vote must be rejected. The next president and vice president must be truly the people's choice. Unfortunately, in the third amendment (to the 1945 Constitution), all factions of the MPR have agreed to the two-step presidential election. Thus, the ongoing debate merely concerns the second vote in direct presidential elections. - Media Indonesia \par \par \uc2  FOREIGN BIZMEN NO LONGER SEE INDONESIA AS CONDUCIVE INVESTMENT DESTINATION \par \par \uc2  There is nothing new in reports that say that both foreign and domestic investments in Indonesia have decreased sharply, especially after the onset of the Asian financial crisis in 1997. Why? Because this country is filled with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  - insecurities, riots, crimes and horizontal conflicts. The latest \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  which has drawn debate is the court verdict against the insurance company, Manulife Indonesia (AJMI). The 1997 crisis not only hit Indonesia but also other Asian states such as South Korea, the Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore. The Asian countries except Indonesia, however, have launched all-out efforts to lure back investors, for instances by offering \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  holidays. South Korea has even predicted that it would totally recover from its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  difficulties this November. What about us? We should improve our country's image so as to bring foreign investors back to Indonesia. We should stop making controversial decisions such as that on the AJMI case. - Kompas. \par \par \uc2 Document antara0020020701dy6t0005l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
