\par\par \b \uc2  New labor bill adding to investors' jitters. \b0\par\par\uc2 725 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  PT Indomobil Sukses Internasional, the country's second largest automaker, had planned to hire some 2,000 new workers this year in response to growing demand at home for automobiles. Now it has put these plans on hold because of increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in employing workers here. \par \par \uc2  Indomobil president commissioner Subronto Laras said on Tuesday this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  was mainly due to unfavorable government policies, which were overly protective of workers at the expense of employers, as reflected in the proposed labor protection bill. \par \par \uc2  "We were planning to hire more workers ... because demand for automobiles will continue to increase, but with the current \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in government policies we decided to postpone the hiring of 2,000 new workers," he told The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2  Subronto was commenting on the much criticized labor protection bill proposed by Minister of Manpower and Transmigration Jacob Nuawea. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  Commission VII for people's welfare and manpower affairs held a hearing with businesspeople on Tuesday to discuss the bill. Representatives of several business associations and investors attended the hearing. \par \par \uc2  During the hearing, the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) proposed revisions to 31 of the bill's 208 clauses, which the association considered to be damaging to the business climate in the country. \par \par \uc2  The clauses stipulate, among other things, that employers must continue to pay the full salaries of striking workers; provide severance pay to workers who voluntarily resign; and cut night-shifts to 35 working hours per week. The clauses also provide for jail terms for violations of labor rulings. \par \par \uc2  Businesspeople said such overly protective rulings would further damage the investment climate at home and scare off investors from the country, which has been struggling to attract foreign investment since the devastating 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investors have already been discouraged by the political, security and regional autonomy problems that have plagued Indonesia over the past several years. \par \par \uc2  "The bill on workers is a substantial issue for investors. If the bill is approved by the House and implemented, then it will be a huge problem for us since the bill provides too much protection for labor at the expense of employers," the secretary-general of the Korean Chamber of Commerce, C.K. Song, told the Post on the sidelines of the hearing. \par \par \uc2  Song runs a footwear manufacturing company here. Currently, his company employs over 10,000 workers at its factory in Tangerang, Banten province. \par \par \uc2  Indomobil's Subronto said that over the past two years, many companies here, including Indomobil, had avoided hiring permanent employees to try and avoid any labor difficulties, and were instead outsourcing their labor needs. \par \par \uc2  He said that of Indomobil's some 8,000 employees, about 1,000 were outsourced. \par \par \uc2  He explained that most companies actually disliked the outsourcing alternative because they had to spend money training workers they would not keep on a permanent basis. \par \par \uc2  Nation in waiting for labor law \par \par \uc2  For more than four years the nation has been waiting for a reliable and trouble-free labor law. \par \par \uc2  In 1997, in the waning days of the Soeharto regime, then minister of manpower Abdul Latief proposed a controversial labor bill, which was roundly criticized by activists for stifling workers' rights. There were also accusations that Latief bribed legislators with money taken from the workers' social security program, Jamsostek, to pass the bill into Law No. 25/1997. \par \par \uc2  After the fall of Soeharto in 1998, then president B.J. Habibie issued Law No. 11/1998 revoking this earlier law until October 2000. \par \par \uc2  In 2000, during the tenure of president Abdurrahman Wahid, then minister of manpower Bomer Pasaribu, along with the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 , drafted two worker bills to replace the controversial Law No. 25/1997. \par \par \uc2  The two bills dealt with labor protection and the settlement of industrial disputes, and allowed for the establishment of a labor court. \par \par \uc2  However, deliberations of the proposed bills were not completed by the deadline of October 2000. \par \par \uc2  The government and the House then issued Law No. 28/2000, which extended Law No. 11/1998 until October 2002. \par \par \uc2  And now, under President Megawati Soekarnoputri, the government is proposing a new labor protection bill. \par \par \uc2  If the House fails to complete the deliberation of the bill by the October deadline, then Law No. 25/1997 will again come into effect. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020703dy730000s\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
