\par\par \b \uc2  Sturdy rupiah - Adrenalin rush for ailing banks. \b0\par\par\uc2 1,092 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  15 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Bernie K. Moestofa, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  Perhaps, it's just a start. For cynics, it remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Either way, it's a sign that good things could be on the horizon. \par \par \uc2  The strengthening rupiah over the past six months already offers hope that could pull local banks out of their five-year depression. \par \par \uc2  A 13 percent rise in the rupiah and a nearly 2 percentage point decrease in \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have already provided room for new loans. \par \par \uc2  "We're seeing improvements in the rupiah affecting the banking sector," said banking analyst Ryan Kiryanto of the Bank Negara Indonesia (BNI). \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , has said that an overall better \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would spur loan growth this year to Rp 62.12 trillion (about US$7.1 billion) from Rp 47.7 trillion in new loans last year. \par \par \uc2  As yet, however, its first quarter report of the banking sector points to some of the same illnesses that banks have been suffering from year after year. \par \par \uc2  At the top of the list is a vulnerable capital adequacy (CAR) ratio, which measures capital against total loans. Banks were required to obtain a minimum CAR of 8 percent by the end of last year as per a \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  decree, which many barely met. \par \par \uc2  Stumbling over the CAR prerequisite, Unibank got the axe while five others, among them Bank Bali, were asked to merge. \par \par \uc2  Those banks lost out despite the government's Rp 630 trillion recapitalization program to halt banks' falling CAR. \par \par \uc2  In the first six months, most banks did not show improvement in earning new money. \par \par \uc2  Research done by Investor magazine last month showed that 24 out of 136 banks booked losses amounting to Rp 465.36 billion. In the same period last year, 22 of 138 banks booked losses amounting to Rp 492.80 billion. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA) was supposed to expedite bank recovery, but its work has been painstakingly slow. \par \par \uc2  Analysts blamed banks' poor performance partly on an adverse \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  throughout 2001. Political instability has kept the rupiah low and volatile for most of the year, and \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates expensively high for loan seekers. \par \par \uc2  President Megawati Soekarnoputri's relatively peaceful rise to power in July 2001 drove the rupiah up only to fall again in the aftermath of the Sept. 11 terrorist strike in the U.S. \par \par \uc2  Abroad, the world's leading economies languished in near recession led by a slump in the U.S. - the world's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Indonesia's biggest export market. \par \par \uc2  With these conditions facing the banking sector, few analysts in late 2001 believed an upturn this year was forthcoming. \par \par \uc2  Six months later, there is reason to hope. A combination of macroeconomic stability and signs of a U.S. recovery have the potential to improve the banking sector, or at least deter a second bank crisis as many had warned about months ago. \par \par \uc2  BNI's Ryan said the outlook had turned from bleak to positive. "I'd say banks are resuming their lending role." \par \par \uc2  As yet, banks' intermediary role in an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is to channel loans to the private sector, remains inadequate. Evidence of this is to be found in banks' low Loan to Deposit (LDR) ratio. \par \par \uc2  According to Ryan, the average bank LDR, which measures a bank's total loans to deposits, stands at about 45 percent. A healthy banking sector can sum up an LDR of around 90 percent and more. \par \par \uc2  But several banks only began significant new lending last year, after being given clearance from \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's loan restriction \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for banks with low CAR levels, he said. \par \par \uc2  While those banks continue to increase their savings deposits, the inability to pass the funds over as loans, dragged down banks' LDR levels. \par \par \uc2  BNI was one example, Ryan said. The state-owned bank's 2001 LDR level was a meager 35 percent after it resumed lending in that year. \par \par \uc2  The strengthening of the rupiah should help banks increase their LDR, he said, explaining that \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's subsequent lower benchmark rates made loans more affordable to the private sector. \par \par \uc2  Still, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's first quarter report showed lending remained sluggish. \par \par \uc2  "Banks are ready to lend, but the question is whether companies are ready to seek new loans," Ryan said. \par \par \uc2  He said banks' traditional clients, large corporations, were still in the process of restructuring their debts and were unfit for new loans. \par \par \uc2  These debts are remnants of the 1997 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, which drove up the cost of debt servicing after the rupiah plunged in value. The rupiah's fall created many non-performing loans and led to the near collapse of the banking sector. \par \par \uc2  As the once fat market has gone dry, banks turn to the less profitable small and medium size enterprises or the consumer sector for lending. \par \par \uc2  Most however stash their funds into \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  promissory notes which although earn lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  than loans, are relatively risk free. \par \par \uc2  Switching back to large corporations was too risky for now, said analyst Baradita Katoppo of the independent research body IBAS. Yet a stronger rupiah not only made loans cheaper, it also served as an incentive to settle foreign debts. \par \par \uc2  "Companies' debt restructuring plans pegged the rupiah at 10,000 against the dollar," Baradita said. \par \par \uc2  At current levels of around 8,700 to the dollar, settling foreign debts would effectively yield a 13 percent discount. \par \par \uc2  Baradita said companies that took the responsibility and paid their outstanding foreign debts should be back in the market for new loans. \par \par \uc2  Whether this is happening remains to be seen. The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment may have improved and banks may also be in better shape to raise lending, but old problems in the banking sector persist. \par \par \uc2  A weak CAR across the sector is putting a strain on banks to extend fresh loans. There is concern that the shaky recovery of the private sector may cause new defaults and yank banks' CAR levels below the required 8 percent. \par \par \uc2  It also explains bank reluctance to cut back their dependence on recapitalization bonds. \par \par \uc2  According to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , some 44 percent of banks' revenue come from the state-funded bonds which earned them less money than if they had invested in loans. \par \par \uc2  Banks also earn less from \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's promissory notes after the stronger rupiah caused benchmark rates to fall. \par \par \uc2  Still, if the rupiah maintains its strength, the currency may lift the banking sector out of the doldrums after sending it there five years ago. \par