\par\par \b \uc2  Rini claims labor unrest is hitting exports. \b0\par\par\uc2 673 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Rendi A. Witular and Adianto P. Simamora, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The increasing number of incidents of labor unrest here has not only affected the flow of foreign direct investment but has also hit the country's export sector, Minister of Industry and Trade Rini MS Soewandi warned. \par \par \uc2  She said on Friday that the latest signs of weakening export performance was mainly attributed to widespread labor protests and security problems. \par \par \uc2  She explained that labor unrest was creating new \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the delivery of goods to overseas buyers. \par \par \uc2  "Many international buyers have decided to shift their orders to other countries because of security and labor problems here," she said. \par \par \uc2  "That's why I have several times expressed my concern on this labor problem to Minister of Manpower and Transmigration Jacob Nuawea and asked him to promptly sort it out," she added. \par \par \uc2  The Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) revealed earlier this week that exports in May were down by 1.5 percent to US$4.7 billion from April, and down 1.85 percent when compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  It was the first signs of the country's weakening export performance after exports had started to rise during the past previous months amid hopes of a quicker \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in the U.S. and Japan, Indonesia's largest export destinations. \par \par \uc2  Exports were behind the impressive 4.8 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2000. Although the government has said this year's 4 percent growth will mainly be driven by domestic consumption, a stronger export performance will be crucial to obtain higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to create more jobs and lower the current high level of unemployment, which according to one estimate has reached 40 million. \par \par \uc2  Electronics, footwear and textiles have suffered a decline in exports during the first five months of this year. The electronics sector saw a decline in exports from $2.6 billion to $2.2 billion; textiles down from $1.2 billion to $1 billion, and footwear dropped from $706 million to $572 million. \par \par \uc2  These industries happen to employ huge numbers of workers and have often experienced trouble with workers' protests. \par \par \uc2  The Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) economist Djisman Simandjuntak agreed with Rini, saying that many overseas buyers of Indonesian exports have shifted to China partly due to local labor conflicts. \par \par \uc2  Other analysts have said that another factor was the sharp increase in the value of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar, which has made Indonesian products less competitive than their Chinese counterparts, which has a fixed exchange rate system. \par \par \uc2  Indonesia is competing with China in the export of low-end manufacturing products like textiles, electronics and footwear. \par \par \uc2  Djisman said that the government must quickly deliver policies that could suppress the seemingly unending labor conflict. He said this could entice new investment into the country's export-oriented industries. \par \par \uc2  But the Minister of Manpower and Transmigration instead drew controversy recently when proposing a new labor protection bill, which many businessmen and investors said was overly protective for workers. They said that if approved, it would scare away investors. \par \par \uc2  Foreign direct investment (FDI) approvals during the first five months of this year dropped by 60 percent to $1.67 billion compared to the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  Chairman of the Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) Theo F. Toemion said that legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and labor unrest were among the factors causing the drop in FDI. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, analyst from Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (INDEF) Bustanul Arifin, disagreed with the accusation that labor unrest was the main factor contributing to the dismal export performance. \par \par \uc2  "It's just ridiculous to blame the workers for this. Rini is just being emotional about the decline. She should elaborate on the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and overall business climate instead of pointing the finger at a scapegoat," said Bustanul. \par \par \uc2  According to Bustanul, the main reason for the weakening exports is mainly due to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown and Indonesia's inability to fulfill buyers' orders. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020709dy760006f\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI warns of negative sentiment a head ST MPR. \b0\par\par\uc2 622 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 July 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  board of governors meeting warns of risk factor and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of MPR (People Consultative Assembly) yearly meeting that might trigger negative sentiments. \par \par \uc2  The governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Syahril Sabirin said despite existing pressures on inflation he was optimistic inflation target of 2002 could be reached. Besides, BI estimated pressures on inflation in the coming months would originate from food supply disturbances due to dry season. \par \par \uc2  "But in the future prospect, the inflation rate of 9% to 10% could be reached," he said in Jakarta yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Governors board meeting concluded that pressures on inflation rate at the second quarter of 2002 were still mounting as the impact of government's price \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  At currency side, the board of governors predicted of a further strengthening space for currencies. However BI warned of the need to be alert on risk factor and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of yearly meeting of MPR. The ST-MPR was expected to raise negative sentiments that could weaken currencies. \par \par \uc2  BI noted the development of consumers price index (CPI) of the first quarter of 2002 of 0.92% (q-t-q). The figures were lower than 3.50% of previous quarter (q-t-q), as year-on-year inflation during this quarter reached 11.48% (y-o-y) \par \par \uc2  According to BI press release the reduction of inflation rate during the second quarter of 2002 was price correction in relation to sufficient supply of goods, improving distribution of goods, dan the strengthening of rupiah. \par \par \uc2  BI said deflation occuring on the first month of second quarter was due to grand harvest season that was supported by the improving goods distribution. \par \par \uc2  However the impact of government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on pricing inflicted pressures so inflation occurred on the end of quarter. \par \par \uc2  Generally speaking, BI board of governors concluded that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the second quarter of 2002 showed an improving development. \par \par \uc2  The indicator was the strengthening of the rupiah, lower inflation rate, and controlled monetary figures. The development pushed interest rate lower and encouraged banking and stock market performances. \par \par \uc2  However this development was insufficient to back up Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \par \par \uc2  To that end BI stressed on the need for coordination with government to speed up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery by maintaining the stability of inflation and currency rates. \par \par \uc2  More focussed \par \par \uc2  Coordinating minister for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti said government and BI would stage coordination at monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors. According to him, the present coordination was at its best as indicated by the controlled inflation. \par \par \uc2  "The present condition paved the way for a more stable rupiah and lower interest rate." \par \par \uc2  Dorodjatun hoped the real sector would grow as government wanted to be more focussed in order to convince domestic and foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  "This is needed to revive neglected projects." \par \par \uc2  Foreign currency up \par \par \uc2  In other development BI announced that the foreign currency supply at the first week of July 2002 reached US$29.77 billion (International Reserve and Foreign Currency Liquidity - at current rate), or up US$466.70 million compared to its position in previous week. \par \par \uc2  "The increase was mostly deriving from the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (BPPN) revenue," Dewi Normawati, a senior analyst said in a press release received by Bisnis Indonesia yesterday. \par \par \uc2  BI disclosed also that he position of primary currency at July 5, 2002 reached Rp121.18 trillion, or up Rp1.24 trillion compared to June 28, 2002 position. The increase, Dewi said, was mostly caused by circulated paper as well as metal money increase due to employee salary payments. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile the open market operation gave impact on Rp4.64 trillion expansion. By the development, BI continued, the net domestic assets of this week exerted contraction impact of Rp2.72 trillion. (aph/ab). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020020710dy7a0005o\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley1