\par\par \b \uc2  Govt sells 3.1% of Telkom stake in privatization push. \b0\par\par\uc2 484 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  13 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \par \uc2  The government announced on Tuesday that it has raised US$126 million from the sale of a 3.1 percent stake in state-owned telecommunications firm PT Telkom through a placement. \par \par \uc2  A statement said that 92 percent of the 312 million shares sold through the placement at Rp 3,635 - which began on Monday night - went to European, Asian and American investors, while the rest went to domestic investors. \par \par \uc2  The sale wrapped up the government's plan to sell 15 percent of its shares in the publicly listed company. \par \par \uc2  Last year, the government sold an 11.9 percent stake in Telkom through a block sale transaction with a price tag of Rp 2,600 per share, raising some $300 million in proceeds. \par \par \uc2  The transaction reduces the government's ownership in the telecom company to 51.2 percent. \par \par \uc2  Previously, the government held a 66.19 percent stake in Telkom, the country's largest telecommunications company and currently holds exclusive rights to local and domestic long distance telephone services. \par \par \uc2  News about the sale prompted the Jakarta Stock Exchange to suspend trading in Telkom in the morning session. It resumed trading in the afternoon session following government confirmation. \par \par \uc2  Telkom's shares closed at Rp 3,775 on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  The sale was part of the government's efforts to sell its ownership in several state-owned enterprises (SOEs) under the privatization program. \par \par \uc2  So far however, progress has been slow with the sale of many SOEs lagging behind schedule. \par \par \uc2  During the first semester, the government only managed to collect some Rp 1 trillion from the sale of state international call operator PT Indosat. \par \par \uc2  In May, it sold 8 percent of its shares in the company through a private placement, falling short of the initial target of 15 percent, which was in part due to a lack of interest by investors and poorly arranged transactions. \par \par \uc2  From the privatization program, the government is hoping to rake in Rp 6.5 trillion, to be used partly to help plug the 2002 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is estimated at more than Rp 42 trillion, or some 2.5 percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP). \par \par \uc2  Aside from the much-needed proceeds, the smooth process of the program will also pave the way for a revival of confidence among investors that the country is going ahead with its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform program. \par \par \uc2  Analysts have welcomed the Telkom sale, saying the transaction should be positive for the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  because it shows that foreign investors remain interested in several of the country's valuable assets. \par \par \uc2  Foreign investor confidence in the country has been thin, with a 60 percent drop in foreign direct investment during the first five months of this year due to various factors including legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the lack of security and labor problems. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020717dy7h0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  BI postpones risk component in CAR. \b0\par\par\uc2 539 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 July 2002\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjourns the implementation of risk component in measuring Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR) scheduled for this year because its regulators level review was yet to be completed. \par \par \uc2  "I think not this year. Kita need more time to make an indepth review. Otherwise a decision would be implemented without an indepth overview," deputy governor of BI Maulana Ibrahim said here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  According to him, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  was worried that if the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was applied this year it could exert bad impact on the improving national banking. "Otherwise it disfavours banks whose condition has been improving at the moment." \par \par \uc2  He added presently the review process, including stress test, was going on at the directorate of banking arrangement at BI. However he was \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  to when the inclusion of risk component at CAR calculation be implemented. \par \par \uc2  According to initial plan, risk component would be included at CAR calculation after the stress test was completed. The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was applied in the framework of international \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Stress test is a test performed by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  on a model of banking risk management using an extreme scenario of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition. The test is conducted in order to know the readiness level of banks at the time BI issues \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the inclusion of market risk as well as operational risk in measuring CAR. \par \par \uc2  CAR drops \par \par \uc2  Up to now the measurement of CAR has only put credit risk into consideration. Based on the stress test result, CAR of several banks was relatively dropping to under 8%. This applied to bank with permanent interest bond, because by the new method of calculation, the dividing component for capital is bigger. \par \par \uc2  According to an official at BI the market risk measurement at CAR component was more crucial than increasing the minimum CAR to 12% later this year. BI, he said, was upgrading the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on market risk measurement on CAR component. \par \par \uc2  The postponement was in line with the press release of Bank for International Settlement's (BIS) saying to adjourn the ruling on bank CAR up to the fourth quarter of 2003. Deadline for the implementation of the new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  at respective countries was also postponed until 2006. \par \par \uc2  During these three years period banks and bank supervisors were expected to adapt and build system and process needed for the application of the new standards. \par \par \uc2  Earlier BIS asserted that this ruling would be completed this very year and to be implemented in 2005. The postponement was attributed to the prominent differences on how to measure loans for small and middle sized credit. \par \par \uc2  BIS said it would go on with the plan to include the operating risk in the measurement of bank capital risk and was seeking to obtain a detailed operating risks with a new approach. \par \par \uc2  BIS would also review the minimum structure of bank CAR. In the new approach, there would be floor limit for capital for the two first years at the time the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  was implemented. \par \par \uc2  As of late 2006 and before the first year of the implementation, the CAR would have had included credit risk and operating risk which were not under 90% of the minimum capital need and in the second year minimum 60% of capital needs. (htr). \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020020718dy7i000b5\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
