\par\par \b \uc2  Watching the U.S. nervously. \b0\par\par\uc2 753 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 July 2002\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  6 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2002 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The rash of corporate and accounting scandals in the United States will surely have a negative impact on Indonesia, which sells more than 22 percent of its exports to the world's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The immediate impact is already discernible in the declining value of the dollar and the almost 5 percent fall in stock prices on Wall Street over the last few days. \par \par \uc2  With an estimated half of all households in the U.S. owning stocks, the wealth effect of falling stock prices is in itself very important, as it will hurt consumer confidence and consequently affect market demand. \par \par \uc2  The core of the problem, as we can see from the financial market performance over the last three days, is the lack of confidence in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This is quite hurtful for the Americans, who have just come off a decade of overwhelming consumer confidence, believing that they had the strongest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and were the most entrepreneurial nation in the world. \par \par \uc2  Equally damaging is falling foreign confidence in the United States financial market. Because its trade \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  with the world is huge, the U.S must attract at least US$1 trillion in foreign money every day. A weakening capital inflow could further drive down the dollar and consequently drive up the prices of imported goods and depress consumer demand. \par \par \uc2  Now that the U.S. is no longer seen as the safest and most profitable place for investment, at least for the time being or until the market is reassured that there will no longer be a new major wave of corporate malfeasance, many analysts reckon that foreign funds will soon search for better places for investment. \par \par \uc2  The dilemma, though, is that investors do not have many other places to go. European \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is expected to remain slower than American growth for the foreseeable future, while Japan remains moribund and emerging markets, such as Indonesia, are seen as fraught with too many risks. \par \par \uc2  No wonder most investors are nervously watching the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But whether the corporate scandals inflict enduring damage on business investment, a key ingredient to a stable, long-lasting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, will depend on the developments within the next few weeks. \par \par \uc2  Among the most determinant factors to restore confidence in the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  are how strong and deep will the U.S. government push ahead with corporate and accounting reforms be and how will investors and the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  react to the forthcoming reports on second-quarter corporate earnings. \par \par \uc2  Most analysts are nevertheless optimistic that U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience is strong enough to survive the "corporate terrorist attacks" as it did immediately after last September's terrorist attacks in New York. \par \par \uc2  How does Indonesia, which is in its fifth year of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, stand amid these developments? \par \par \uc2  Certainly, the external factor is now less favorable for Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , meaning that exports, currently the largest generator of growth besides consumer demand, is much more difficult. Now that the U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospect is rather \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the country should launch a more concerted effort to promote exports to other markets to offset the expected lower demand from the American market. \par \par \uc2  But exporting is only the end of a chain of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, which consists mainly of the import of industrial materials, the production process and transportation. \par \par \uc2  Unfortunately, all these chains are still beset with problems that directly affect export competitiveness. Imports are still having to struggle with a corrupt, inefficient customs service and transportation is suffering from a crumbling infrastructure. \par \par \uc2  Most damaging is labor unrest, which disturbs production operations and makes foreign buyers less confident about timely deliveries from Indonesian exporters. \par \par \uc2  The government, however, does not seem fully aware of how crucial exports are for fueling a sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, as can be seen in the absence of well-coordinated programs to bolster exports. \par \par \uc2  The government should realize that consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the largest generator of growth since 2000, will eventually lose steam without a steady increase in income to build up savings. Investment, which is supposed to be the other ingredient for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  expansion, is still hard to come by without significant improvement in law enforcement, security conditions, a smooth implementation of regional autonomy and labor relations. \par \par \uc2  Exporting, therefore, is now the best alternative to generate a sustainable recovery. But exports will never grow markedly unless the Cabinet corrects its fatally mistaken perception that exporting is the sole responsibility of the Ministry of Trade and Industry. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 2002 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020020719dy7j0000b\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft